WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.547 --> 00:00:07.880
DAVE BARRY: It's nice to be
here, at Google in New York.

00:00:07.880 --> 00:00:13.080
I actually have done a couple
of events at Mountain View,

00:00:13.080 --> 00:00:16.260
including one where I performed.

00:00:16.260 --> 00:00:21.420
I'm in a rock band of authors,
with Stephen King, Amy Tan,

00:00:21.420 --> 00:00:24.427
Mitch Albom, Ridley Pearson,
Greg Iles, Roy Blount Jr.,

00:00:24.427 --> 00:00:25.010
Scott Thoreau.

00:00:25.010 --> 00:00:25.967
A bunch of authors.

00:00:25.967 --> 00:00:27.050
They're very good authors.

00:00:27.050 --> 00:00:29.620
We're a horrible band.

00:00:29.620 --> 00:00:32.040
We play-- Roy Blount
has described our genre

00:00:32.040 --> 00:00:34.980
as hard listening music.

00:00:34.980 --> 00:00:39.209
And I say we play-- I call
it the rumor method of music,

00:00:39.209 --> 00:00:41.500
which is everybody in the
band is holding an instrument

00:00:41.500 --> 00:00:43.472
and playing something.

00:00:43.472 --> 00:00:45.180
And then a rumor goes
around that there's

00:00:45.180 --> 00:00:46.350
been a chord change.

00:00:46.350 --> 00:00:47.432
Whoa, you know.

00:00:47.432 --> 00:00:48.890
And we all switch
to another chord,

00:00:48.890 --> 00:00:52.090
but not necessarily
the same other chord.

00:00:52.090 --> 00:00:55.174
But anyway, we spent a
day in Mountain View.

00:00:55.174 --> 00:00:56.090
That was a lot of fun.

00:00:56.090 --> 00:00:58.630
They give us this
detailed elaborate tour,

00:00:58.630 --> 00:01:00.960
and gave us no
information at all.

00:01:00.960 --> 00:01:03.090
I think it's a Google thing.

00:01:03.090 --> 00:01:04.940
Like we would say, are
there any questions?

00:01:04.940 --> 00:01:08.150
And we'd go, how many
servers do you have?

00:01:08.150 --> 00:01:09.765
And they go, we
can't tell you that.

00:01:09.765 --> 00:01:11.100
Where's the electricity come?

00:01:11.100 --> 00:01:12.058
We can't tell you that.

00:01:12.058 --> 00:01:15.740
So anyway, the food was great.

00:01:15.740 --> 00:01:17.580
And the cafeteria was great.

00:01:17.580 --> 00:01:21.130
And Sergey and Larry
were there dancing to us.

00:01:21.130 --> 00:01:25.087
So it was a fun experience.

00:01:25.087 --> 00:01:26.420
I'm going to talk about my book.

00:01:26.420 --> 00:01:29.910
My book actually has a
major Google component,

00:01:29.910 --> 00:01:33.240
which I will get to after
I've softened you up,

00:01:33.240 --> 00:01:35.540
and hope that you don't hate me.

00:01:35.540 --> 00:01:36.580
So I can talk about it.

00:01:36.580 --> 00:01:41.730
But it's a series of essays on
a bunch of different topics.

00:01:41.730 --> 00:01:44.660
The title is meaningless, as is
true of almost all of my books.

00:01:44.660 --> 00:01:47.100
I write what I think
are funny essays,

00:01:47.100 --> 00:01:49.470
and then the publisher
says, well, we need a title.

00:01:49.470 --> 00:01:50.630
We need a theme.

00:01:50.630 --> 00:01:53.390
And we sort of make one
up at the last minute,

00:01:53.390 --> 00:01:55.800
and that becomes the
title of the book.

00:01:55.800 --> 00:01:58.320
Although there is
there a sort of roughly

00:01:58.320 --> 00:02:00.220
a kind of a happiness
and unhappiness

00:02:00.220 --> 00:02:02.270
element to the book.

00:02:02.270 --> 00:02:04.060
But mainly it's a
series of essays.

00:02:04.060 --> 00:02:08.520
The first one is called
"Bite Me, David Beckham."

00:02:08.520 --> 00:02:14.880
And it is based on the fact
that my wife is a soccer writer.

00:02:14.880 --> 00:02:16.860
She's a sportswriter
for the "Miami Herald,"

00:02:16.860 --> 00:02:18.260
and she covers soccer.

00:02:18.260 --> 00:02:19.960
Covers the World Cup.

00:02:19.960 --> 00:02:21.560
Does a lot of soccer stuff.

00:02:21.560 --> 00:02:25.097
And David Beckham,
who is considered

00:02:25.097 --> 00:02:26.680
by many people--
including, I believe,

00:02:26.680 --> 00:02:29.750
my wife-- the handsomest
person on the planet,

00:02:29.750 --> 00:02:32.510
is trying to start a
soccer team in Miami.

00:02:32.510 --> 00:02:35.940
And so he is sort of wooing the
whole city of Miami, including

00:02:35.940 --> 00:02:36.760
the media.

00:02:36.760 --> 00:02:40.590
And my wife is the main
soccer writer in Miami.

00:02:40.590 --> 00:02:44.239
So she spends an
inordinate amount of time

00:02:44.239 --> 00:02:45.030
with David Beckham.

00:02:45.030 --> 00:02:48.940
Now that ordinarily wouldn't
cause me any insecurity all,

00:02:48.940 --> 00:02:52.920
except that I've never been
really good about how I look.

00:02:52.920 --> 00:02:56.930
And I explain, in the book, why
I'm insecure about my looks.

00:02:56.930 --> 00:02:59.240
And one of the
things I do-- I went

00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:01.120
to Pleasantville High
School, right up, not

00:03:01.120 --> 00:03:02.330
too far from here.

00:03:02.330 --> 00:03:05.790
I graduated, class of 1965,
Pleasantville High School.

00:03:05.790 --> 00:03:09.360
And I want to show you why
I'm insecure about my looks.

00:03:09.360 --> 00:03:11.550
This is my high
school yearbook photo.

00:03:15.270 --> 00:03:15.770
OK?

00:03:15.770 --> 00:03:18.610
That is the best I could do.

00:03:18.610 --> 00:03:21.470
That wasn't me on a bad day.

00:03:21.470 --> 00:03:24.520
This is me looking
as good as I can

00:03:24.520 --> 00:03:26.470
in high school-- as a
senior in high school.

00:03:26.470 --> 00:03:30.470
I've got, like,
Soviet Union glasses.

00:03:30.470 --> 00:03:34.129
Which now, are,
like, retro and hip.

00:03:34.129 --> 00:03:35.920
I'd like to punch the
hipsters in the mouth

00:03:35.920 --> 00:03:38.086
when they put these glasses
on ironically, because I

00:03:38.086 --> 00:03:40.710
had to wear them.

00:03:40.710 --> 00:03:41.990
Also, note my hair.

00:03:41.990 --> 00:03:43.630
Just a quick note
of my hairstyle.

00:03:43.630 --> 00:03:45.046
I'm not saying
it's wonderful now,

00:03:45.046 --> 00:03:46.940
but it was really bad then.

00:03:46.940 --> 00:03:48.850
My dad cut my hair.

00:03:48.850 --> 00:03:52.864
And my dad was a professional
Presbyterian minister.

00:03:52.864 --> 00:03:54.530
And he was a good
Presbyterian minister,

00:03:54.530 --> 00:03:58.245
but they don't train
them in hair design.

00:03:58.245 --> 00:04:00.830
But he bought a pair of--
he worked in New York City,

00:04:00.830 --> 00:04:05.710
bought a pair of hair clippers
at Grand Central Station,

00:04:05.710 --> 00:04:08.960
and that's how he cut my
brothers' and my hair.

00:04:08.960 --> 00:04:12.410
And I agree that we should
get assault rifles out

00:04:12.410 --> 00:04:15.432
of the hands of the
American public,

00:04:15.432 --> 00:04:17.390
but first we need to get
the hair clippers away

00:04:17.390 --> 00:04:19.670
from the dads who are
still cutting hair.

00:04:19.670 --> 00:04:23.505
So anyway, I write an essay
about the awkwardness,

00:04:23.505 --> 00:04:28.192
the insecurity, of looking
like that as a kid.

00:04:28.192 --> 00:04:30.400
And it sort of sticks with
you the rest of your life,

00:04:30.400 --> 00:04:32.640
the image you form
of yourself as a kid.

00:04:32.640 --> 00:04:36.150
And now having to deal
with David Beckham

00:04:36.150 --> 00:04:40.350
suddenly being really interested
in impressing my wife.

00:04:40.350 --> 00:04:42.770
I was just going to read
you one little part of it.

00:04:42.770 --> 00:04:45.650
After I show, in the book, the
picture of my high school year

00:04:45.650 --> 00:04:46.920
book, I say--

00:04:46.920 --> 00:04:48.570
Anyway, my point is
that in high school

00:04:48.570 --> 00:04:51.750
I was not physically attractive
to the opposite sex, namely

00:04:51.750 --> 00:04:52.810
girls.

00:04:52.810 --> 00:04:55.624
But, Dave, I hear you remarking,
looks aren't everything.

00:04:55.624 --> 00:04:57.790
There are plenty of other
qualities besides cuteness

00:04:57.790 --> 00:04:59.550
that girls look for in boys.

00:04:59.550 --> 00:05:00.400
Good point.

00:05:00.400 --> 00:05:04.800
And when I say good point, I
mean you are a stupid idiot.

00:05:04.800 --> 00:05:07.560
The girls at
Pleasantville High School

00:05:07.560 --> 00:05:10.000
were not interested in, quote,
plenty of other qualities

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:11.240
besides cuteness.

00:05:11.240 --> 00:05:13.450
I know this, because I had
plenty of other qualities

00:05:13.450 --> 00:05:14.700
besides cuteness.

00:05:14.700 --> 00:05:16.400
Sarcasm, for example.

00:05:16.400 --> 00:05:18.890
I had a black belt in sarcasm.

00:05:18.890 --> 00:05:20.930
I went entire years without
ever saying anything

00:05:20.930 --> 00:05:23.180
that was not basically the
opposite of what I actually

00:05:23.180 --> 00:05:24.210
thought.

00:05:24.210 --> 00:05:27.740
Also, I could make realistic
farting sounds with my hands.

00:05:27.740 --> 00:05:30.240
These are just two of the many
qualities other than cuteness

00:05:30.240 --> 00:05:31.700
I had in high school.

00:05:31.700 --> 00:05:33.320
None of them impressed girls.

00:05:33.320 --> 00:05:35.680
You will never hear a high
school girl say about a boy,

00:05:35.680 --> 00:05:38.115
in a dreamy voice,
he's so sarcastic.

00:05:42.220 --> 00:05:46.390
I have an essay, also, about--
it's a letter to my daughter.

00:05:46.390 --> 00:05:48.810
I have a 15-year-old
daughter, Sophie.

00:05:48.810 --> 00:05:50.710
And she's just turned 15.

00:05:50.710 --> 00:05:55.650
And so she is eligible for
a Florida driving permit.

00:05:55.650 --> 00:05:57.970
And so I've written
a letter to her,

00:05:57.970 --> 00:06:00.920
which begins, "Dear Sophie, so
you're about to start driving.

00:06:00.920 --> 00:06:02.010
How exciting.

00:06:02.010 --> 00:06:04.390
I'm going to kill myself."

00:06:04.390 --> 00:06:07.360
I say this because
I live in Miami.

00:06:07.360 --> 00:06:09.910
I moved there in 1986
from the United States.

00:06:12.750 --> 00:06:13.900
There are many adjustments.

00:06:13.900 --> 00:06:15.880
And Miami isn't as
dangerous as it used to be.

00:06:15.880 --> 00:06:16.645
People worry about that.

00:06:16.645 --> 00:06:19.061
We have a new attitude down
there, a new tourism promotion

00:06:19.061 --> 00:06:24.470
slogan-- come back to Miami,
we weren't shooting you.

00:06:24.470 --> 00:06:29.254
But the driving is still
quite an adventure in Miami.

00:06:29.254 --> 00:06:30.670
When I first got
there, I thought,

00:06:30.670 --> 00:06:32.580
nobody here knows the law.

00:06:32.580 --> 00:06:34.130
I now realize that
everybody in Miami

00:06:34.130 --> 00:06:36.750
is driving according to
the law-- of his or her

00:06:36.750 --> 00:06:38.164
individual country of origin.

00:06:38.164 --> 00:06:40.330
And there are some countries
where, apparently, it's

00:06:40.330 --> 00:06:42.396
traditional to put on
the left turn signal

00:06:42.396 --> 00:06:43.520
first thing in the morning.

00:06:46.187 --> 00:06:47.770
Maybe put it on the
night before, just

00:06:47.770 --> 00:06:49.132
to make sure it's working.

00:06:49.132 --> 00:06:50.590
It's the only place
I've ever lived

00:06:50.590 --> 00:06:54.110
where the driver's manual shows
you how to give the finger.

00:06:54.110 --> 00:06:58.170
Or people will pass
you in a car wash.

00:06:58.170 --> 00:07:01.495
And I know you guys are
working on self-driving cars,

00:07:01.495 --> 00:07:02.370
I think that's great.

00:07:02.370 --> 00:07:04.940
We already have that in Miami.

00:07:04.940 --> 00:07:09.350
If you drive in Miami, you'll
see many like, no head at all,

00:07:09.350 --> 00:07:10.420
just hands.

00:07:10.420 --> 00:07:13.650
These are seniors,
on the road of Miami.

00:07:13.650 --> 00:07:15.820
There's a lot of folks down
there, senior citizens.

00:07:15.820 --> 00:07:18.760
A lot of them from here, from
New York, who I don't think

00:07:18.760 --> 00:07:20.450
drove a lot most of their lives.

00:07:20.450 --> 00:07:22.280
I think they took
public transportation.

00:07:22.280 --> 00:07:24.550
Then they moved
to south Florida,

00:07:24.550 --> 00:07:27.620
and lost the vast majority
of their sight and hearing,

00:07:27.620 --> 00:07:28.890
and got driver's licenses.

00:07:28.890 --> 00:07:33.380
Which down there come
with your Happy Meal.

00:07:33.380 --> 00:07:38.700
This actually happened, there
was a-- you can Google this,

00:07:38.700 --> 00:07:40.890
in fact.

00:07:40.890 --> 00:07:43.110
Miami police stopped
a 72-year-old man

00:07:43.110 --> 00:07:45.760
driving a Chevrolet Cobalt,
which in itself is not

00:07:45.760 --> 00:07:47.700
so unusual.

00:07:47.700 --> 00:07:49.650
It's where they stopped him.

00:07:49.650 --> 00:07:54.300
And this is true-- runway nine,
Miami International Airport.

00:07:54.300 --> 00:07:56.220
This man burst through
the perimeter gate

00:07:56.220 --> 00:07:58.011
without realizing it,
and was on the runway

00:07:58.011 --> 00:07:59.734
when they stopped him.

00:07:59.734 --> 00:08:01.400
Which, to me, shows
a lack of awareness.

00:08:05.470 --> 00:08:09.670
If I'm driving, and I
realize I'm tailgating a 757,

00:08:09.670 --> 00:08:12.580
I would say, I'm not on
the expressway anymore.

00:08:12.580 --> 00:08:13.570
But he was out there.

00:08:13.570 --> 00:08:17.390
And the thing is,
that's my airport.

00:08:17.390 --> 00:08:20.810
I can't get near a plane,
there, with shampoo.

00:08:20.810 --> 00:08:23.002
This man was out
there with a Cobalt.

00:08:23.002 --> 00:08:27.770
But anyway, we have
a lot of seniors.

00:08:27.770 --> 00:08:31.530
And we also have a lot
of people who drive--

00:08:31.530 --> 00:08:35.159
this is, again, the seniors.

00:08:35.159 --> 00:08:38.370
They divide the labor of
the driving, older couples.

00:08:38.370 --> 00:08:40.919
And I have been in the car
with couples like this.

00:08:40.919 --> 00:08:46.160
The man drives,
but the woman sees.

00:08:46.160 --> 00:08:47.820
He can't see
anymore, but he still

00:08:47.820 --> 00:08:50.200
drives, because that's
what the man does.

00:08:50.200 --> 00:08:52.510
So she's in the, you know,
the passenger seat, going,

00:08:52.510 --> 00:08:54.320
Harry, the light,
it's a green arrow.

00:08:54.320 --> 00:08:54.820
Green arrow.

00:08:54.820 --> 00:08:55.640
No, no, red, red.

00:08:55.640 --> 00:08:58.034
And that's how they--

00:08:58.034 --> 00:08:59.700
Anyway, this is the
environment in which

00:08:59.700 --> 00:09:01.410
my daughter-- I have
to introduce-- she's

00:09:01.410 --> 00:09:03.110
legally going to be
allowed to drive in.

00:09:03.110 --> 00:09:06.180
And I point out in
my letter to her

00:09:06.180 --> 00:09:09.670
that just because the state of
Florida thinks she can drive,

00:09:09.670 --> 00:09:12.110
that doesn't mean-- I mean,
Florida, as far as I can tell,

00:09:12.110 --> 00:09:14.710
there's nobody it
doesn't think can drive.

00:09:14.710 --> 00:09:16.796
If alien beings arrive
here from another planet,

00:09:16.796 --> 00:09:18.420
they'll have Florida
driver's licenses.

00:09:18.420 --> 00:09:21.340
The only thing we will
know for sure about them.

00:09:21.340 --> 00:09:24.100
So anyway, I wrote a letter to
her explaining how to drive.

00:09:24.100 --> 00:09:26.490
And I, in there, discuss
the Florida drivers manual,

00:09:26.490 --> 00:09:30.090
which is a festival
of misinformation.

00:09:30.090 --> 00:09:33.940
It states, for example, that if
there is no marked speed limit,

00:09:33.940 --> 00:09:36.770
you're supposed to
go 35 miles an hour.

00:09:36.770 --> 00:09:41.440
If you do that in Miami,
you will receive gunfire

00:09:41.440 --> 00:09:43.280
from behind you.

00:09:43.280 --> 00:09:48.580
So I have a Q&amp;A
in here, designed

00:09:48.580 --> 00:09:51.010
to help my daughter understand
how driving actually

00:09:51.010 --> 00:09:53.010
works in the state of
Florida, as opposed to how

00:09:53.010 --> 00:09:54.400
the driver's manual says.

00:09:54.400 --> 00:09:56.750
And I'll just read you
a couple of Q&amp;A from it.

00:09:56.750 --> 00:09:59.770
Q, How is the turn
signal used in Florida?

00:09:59.770 --> 00:10:02.760
A, It is used to indicate
other motorists that you do not

00:10:02.760 --> 00:10:06.220
realize your turn
signal is blinking.

00:10:06.220 --> 00:10:08.540
Q, Could it also be used
to signal your intention

00:10:08.540 --> 00:10:10.790
to change lanes?

00:10:10.790 --> 00:10:14.400
A, Interesting nobody
has ever tried that.

00:10:14.400 --> 00:10:17.270
Q, What is the best kind of
food to eat while driving?

00:10:17.270 --> 00:10:20.380
A, Any food, such as a
sandwich, turkey leg, oyster,

00:10:20.380 --> 00:10:22.490
or Ding Dong that
can be eaten one

00:10:22.490 --> 00:10:24.795
handed, so you still have
a hand free for texting.

00:10:27.680 --> 00:10:29.460
Q, What if an
emergency situation

00:10:29.460 --> 00:10:33.710
arises that might require me
to operate the steering wheel?

00:10:33.710 --> 00:10:36.180
A, Use your forehead
to honk the horn

00:10:36.180 --> 00:10:39.490
until the emergency has passed.

00:10:39.490 --> 00:10:41.820
Q, My car's engine
seems to have stopped,

00:10:41.820 --> 00:10:44.130
and I hear a burbling noise.

00:10:44.130 --> 00:10:46.690
A, Are you a senior citizen?

00:10:46.690 --> 00:10:47.960
Q, Yes.

00:10:47.960 --> 00:10:50.240
A, You have driven
into a swimming pool.

00:10:53.230 --> 00:10:57.020
Q, I've had a few drinks, how
can I tell if I should drive?

00:10:57.020 --> 00:11:00.470
A, Take this simple test, are
you wearing your underpants

00:11:00.470 --> 00:11:01.730
on your head?

00:11:01.730 --> 00:11:05.190
Q, Not my underpants, no.

00:11:05.190 --> 00:11:07.950
A, Then you are good to go.

00:11:07.950 --> 00:11:10.660
Q, What's all that shouting?

00:11:10.660 --> 00:11:12.580
A, Are you a senior citizen?

00:11:12.580 --> 00:11:14.000
Q, Yes.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:15.745
A, You have struck a pedestrian.

00:11:18.450 --> 00:11:22.000
There's an essay, I call
it "The Real Mad Men,"

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:25.540
which is about my
parents' generation.

00:11:25.540 --> 00:11:28.380
I'm a baby boomer, I'm
way older than all of you.

00:11:28.380 --> 00:11:32.080
But my parents were
even older than I was.

00:11:32.080 --> 00:11:34.160
They were the
greatest generation.

00:11:34.160 --> 00:11:38.510
And what got me, writing this
essay, was watching the TV

00:11:38.510 --> 00:11:40.578
show "Mad Men," which I
think is a great TV show.

00:11:40.578 --> 00:11:42.286
And on "Mad Men," if
you've ever seen it,

00:11:42.286 --> 00:11:44.050
you know that everybody drinks
and smokes all the time.

00:11:44.050 --> 00:11:45.050
Which I do remember.

00:11:45.050 --> 00:11:45.970
It was very accurate.

00:11:45.970 --> 00:11:47.460
My parents drank and
smoked like crazy,

00:11:47.460 --> 00:11:48.751
and all their friends did, too.

00:11:48.751 --> 00:11:51.310
And then they got in
cars, and did everything

00:11:51.310 --> 00:11:53.120
we're not supposed to do.

00:11:53.120 --> 00:11:55.880
But in "Mad Men" everybody's
always kind of depressed,

00:11:55.880 --> 00:11:57.170
and full of anxiety.

00:11:57.170 --> 00:11:59.280
And at what I remember
about my parents--

00:11:59.280 --> 00:12:01.570
we lived in Armonk,
up in Westchester

00:12:01.570 --> 00:12:03.677
County-- was that they
weren't depressed.

00:12:03.677 --> 00:12:04.760
That they had great times.

00:12:04.760 --> 00:12:06.360
They had wonderful parties.

00:12:06.360 --> 00:12:10.620
They had parties long
after they had us, that's

00:12:10.620 --> 00:12:12.120
how I know they had them.

00:12:12.120 --> 00:12:14.135
We would sit and watch
them drink and smoke,

00:12:14.135 --> 00:12:15.260
and just have a great time.

00:12:15.260 --> 00:12:18.452
And sing and dance, and
do all these things.

00:12:18.452 --> 00:12:20.910
And it occurred to me that my
generation, the baby boomers,

00:12:20.910 --> 00:12:21.630
stopped doing that stuff.

00:12:21.630 --> 00:12:23.602
We all did, you know--
sex, drugs, and rock 'n'

00:12:23.602 --> 00:12:25.584
roll-- until we had kids.

00:12:25.584 --> 00:12:27.000
And then we just
suddenly stopped,

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:29.650
and became this very
serious kind of parent

00:12:29.650 --> 00:12:32.800
that was into parenting, which
is a verb my parents would

00:12:32.800 --> 00:12:35.860
never have used.

00:12:35.860 --> 00:12:38.050
And we spent the
rest of our lives

00:12:38.050 --> 00:12:40.500
trying to parent our
children, and remove

00:12:40.500 --> 00:12:41.970
all the obstacles
from their paths,

00:12:41.970 --> 00:12:43.710
and helicopter around them.

00:12:43.710 --> 00:12:46.065
And, you know, follow them
around trick-or-treating,

00:12:46.065 --> 00:12:48.398
and pounce on them in case
they got something dangerous,

00:12:48.398 --> 00:12:50.311
like an apple.

00:12:50.311 --> 00:12:51.560
And my parents didn't do that.

00:12:51.560 --> 00:12:52.934
They didn't do
any of that stuff.

00:12:52.934 --> 00:12:54.450
They didn't take
us to play dates.

00:12:54.450 --> 00:12:55.190
They sent us out to play.

00:12:55.190 --> 00:12:56.660
They didn't know where we were.

00:12:56.660 --> 00:12:59.280
They served us gluten.

00:12:59.280 --> 00:12:59.850
Openly.

00:12:59.850 --> 00:13:01.350
Openly, people did
gluten back then.

00:13:03.900 --> 00:13:05.712
So I talked about that.

00:13:05.712 --> 00:13:07.920
And there's a whole essay
about the difference, then,

00:13:07.920 --> 00:13:10.370
between my parents'
generation and mine.

00:13:10.370 --> 00:13:13.050
In which mine doesn't
compare particularly well.

00:13:13.050 --> 00:13:16.180
There's a long essay
about Brazil and soccer.

00:13:16.180 --> 00:13:18.200
As I said, my wife's
a soccer writer.

00:13:18.200 --> 00:13:19.740
And she goes the World Cup.

00:13:19.740 --> 00:13:23.610
And I've gone to the
last two World Cups.

00:13:23.610 --> 00:13:27.544
And my daughter, who's 15,
plays on a travel soccer team.

00:13:27.544 --> 00:13:29.960
I don't know if any of you
have ever played travel soccer,

00:13:29.960 --> 00:13:32.600
but the basic idea,
is every weekend

00:13:32.600 --> 00:13:35.270
you get in the car
drive 200 miles,

00:13:35.270 --> 00:13:39.230
to play another team that also
got a car and drove 200 miles,

00:13:39.230 --> 00:13:41.584
sometimes starting at
the same place you did.

00:13:41.584 --> 00:13:44.000
And the reason you do that,
is you have to play in a place

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:46.499
where there's a chance somebody
will be killed by lightning.

00:13:46.499 --> 00:13:49.180
Because the rule in Florida is,
you cannot play soccer unless

00:13:49.180 --> 00:13:50.500
it's under heavy downpours.

00:13:50.500 --> 00:13:54.630
If we ever want to really do
something serious to eliminate

00:13:54.630 --> 00:13:57.850
the drought in California,
or sub-Saharan Africa,

00:13:57.850 --> 00:14:01.060
schedule my daughter's soccer
team there, and it will rain.

00:14:01.060 --> 00:14:03.580
It will rain for days and days.

00:14:03.580 --> 00:14:08.170
Anyway, so I talk, in the book,
about Brazil, about soccer,

00:14:08.170 --> 00:14:09.180
about the World Cup.

00:14:09.180 --> 00:14:10.770
And why I love soccer.

00:14:10.770 --> 00:14:12.160
I've become a the
big soccer fan.

00:14:12.160 --> 00:14:16.070
But also acknowledge the
criticisms that are usually

00:14:16.070 --> 00:14:18.430
leveled at soccer by people.

00:14:18.430 --> 00:14:21.260
Many Americans who
detest the sport.

00:14:21.260 --> 00:14:24.870
And I'll just give you a couple
of the criticisms I list here.

00:14:24.870 --> 00:14:28.051
The players sport haircuts--
I'm talking about pro soccer.

00:14:28.051 --> 00:14:30.050
The players sport hair
cuts that were apparently

00:14:30.050 --> 00:14:32.390
administered by a blind heroin
addict in the men's room

00:14:32.390 --> 00:14:35.269
of a Bulgarian disco in 1978.

00:14:35.269 --> 00:14:36.810
Whenever they collide
with something,

00:14:36.810 --> 00:14:39.590
such as another player,
a tallish blade of grass,

00:14:39.590 --> 00:14:41.560
or an unusually
dense patch of air,

00:14:41.560 --> 00:14:44.060
they try to draw a foul by
hurling themselves dramatically

00:14:44.060 --> 00:14:47.970
to the turf, grabbing a random
knee-- it's always a knee--

00:14:47.970 --> 00:14:51.090
and adopting the agonized
facial expression of a man being

00:14:51.090 --> 00:14:54.260
castrated by irate lobsters.

00:14:54.260 --> 00:14:56.060
Not to single out
any specific nation,

00:14:56.060 --> 00:14:58.220
but there are Italian
players who spend enough time

00:14:58.220 --> 00:15:00.880
lying on the ground to be
biologically classified

00:15:00.880 --> 00:15:03.770
as zucchini.

00:15:03.770 --> 00:15:09.150
I talk about homeownership,
which is the unhappiness

00:15:09.150 --> 00:15:10.560
part of the happiness book.

00:15:10.560 --> 00:15:13.590
And in an essay that
is titled, Everything I

00:15:13.590 --> 00:15:17.630
Know About Homeownership, I
Learned From Johnny Carson.

00:15:17.630 --> 00:15:21.480
And it's actually,
it was a true story.

00:15:21.480 --> 00:15:24.170
The first humor book I
wrote was in the early '80s,

00:15:24.170 --> 00:15:26.360
and it was called "The
Taming of the Screw," which

00:15:26.360 --> 00:15:30.650
was a parity of a
do-it-yourself book.

00:15:30.650 --> 00:15:33.850
And it was kind of a funny
book tour, because at the time,

00:15:33.850 --> 00:15:35.840
I was completely
unknown as a humorist.

00:15:35.840 --> 00:15:38.540
And when I went on tour, many
of the radio stations I went to

00:15:38.540 --> 00:15:42.190
thought I was a serious
home do-it-yourself guy.

00:15:42.190 --> 00:15:44.950
Which made for
some pretty-- like,

00:15:44.950 --> 00:15:49.030
I was across from a guy
in, I believe, St. Louis.

00:15:49.030 --> 00:15:51.264
A radio guy, been on
radio a million years,

00:15:51.264 --> 00:15:53.430
and I was just another
interview he was going to do.

00:15:53.430 --> 00:15:54.180
Another interview.

00:15:54.180 --> 00:15:56.270
And his eyes were bloodshot,
I'm pretty sure he'd

00:15:56.270 --> 00:15:57.600
been drinking at lunch.

00:15:57.600 --> 00:16:00.160
And he's thinking, OK, here's
the do-it-yourself book guy,

00:16:00.160 --> 00:16:02.830
I'll just ask him a question,
and he'll just take it,

00:16:02.830 --> 00:16:03.912
and it'll be over.

00:16:03.912 --> 00:16:06.370
And his first question to me
is, so I see-- and he's, like,

00:16:06.370 --> 00:16:08.536
opening the book for the
first time ever in history,

00:16:08.536 --> 00:16:11.360
for him-- so you talk
about insulating your home.

00:16:11.360 --> 00:16:12.970
What do you say about that?

00:16:12.970 --> 00:16:15.765
And I go, well, the best place
to put it is on your driveway.

00:16:18.380 --> 00:16:19.132
And he goes, what?

00:16:19.132 --> 00:16:20.090
Well, it's just easier.

00:16:20.090 --> 00:16:22.345
Because if you go up in the
attic, it's like, spiders.

00:16:22.345 --> 00:16:24.136
Just put it on your
driveway, and you still

00:16:24.136 --> 00:16:25.020
get the tax credit.

00:16:27.740 --> 00:16:30.210
So he realized what--
anyway I was that kind.

00:16:30.210 --> 00:16:35.800
But the first interview I did,
the first actual book tour

00:16:35.800 --> 00:16:38.800
event I did, and the first time
I was ever, ever on television

00:16:38.800 --> 00:16:41.580
anywhere-- local or national,
any television showw--

00:16:41.580 --> 00:16:44.950
was on the Johnny Carson
show, for this book.

00:16:44.950 --> 00:16:47.676
I'm really not, to
this day, sure exactly

00:16:47.676 --> 00:16:50.050
how that happened, but somehow
my little humor book ended

00:16:50.050 --> 00:16:51.424
up in the hands
of a Tonight Show

00:16:51.424 --> 00:16:53.310
producer named Shirley Wood.

00:16:53.310 --> 00:16:56.660
She was this tough old
broad, chain smoking.

00:16:56.660 --> 00:16:59.140
And she calls me up and goes,
I think your book's funny.

00:16:59.140 --> 00:16:59.830
I go, thank you.

00:16:59.830 --> 00:17:01.100
And she goes, are you funny?

00:17:01.100 --> 00:17:02.490
You know?

00:17:02.490 --> 00:17:04.930
And that's really, actually
what she sounded like.

00:17:04.930 --> 00:17:07.263
That's actually a little more
feminine than she sounded.

00:17:10.859 --> 00:17:12.609
She asked me some
questions, and she said,

00:17:12.609 --> 00:17:13.619
OK, remember these answers.

00:17:13.619 --> 00:17:14.660
And then she flew me out.

00:17:14.660 --> 00:17:17.380
They flew me out to Los Angeles.

00:17:17.380 --> 00:17:21.220
And this is-- I've never been
on television for anything.

00:17:21.220 --> 00:17:23.270
And that was my first, again.

00:17:23.270 --> 00:17:24.630
She came back stage.

00:17:24.630 --> 00:17:28.920
I'm in a green room, I'm in
the backstage dressing room

00:17:28.920 --> 00:17:30.140
next to The Pointer Sisters.

00:17:30.140 --> 00:17:31.098
I'll never forget this.

00:17:31.098 --> 00:17:33.410
Like, The Pointer
Sisters, Dave Barry.

00:17:33.410 --> 00:17:36.200
That was my experience.

00:17:36.200 --> 00:17:38.659
And Shirley Wood comes into
my dressing room and goes,

00:17:38.659 --> 00:17:40.450
do you remember what
you're supposed to do?

00:17:40.450 --> 00:17:41.210
Yeah, yeah.

00:17:41.210 --> 00:17:41.710
Drink this.

00:17:41.710 --> 00:17:43.930
And she hands me
a glass of wine.

00:17:43.930 --> 00:17:47.900
Not like a little glass, a
water glass full of wine.

00:17:47.900 --> 00:17:48.910
And made me drink it.

00:17:48.910 --> 00:17:51.700
And that's how I-- really--
and that's how I went out.

00:17:51.700 --> 00:17:53.620
So I go out, and I
had a seven minute

00:17:53.620 --> 00:17:55.110
spot on "The Tonight Show."

00:17:55.110 --> 00:17:57.170
They don't do that much
anymore, where they

00:17:57.170 --> 00:17:59.050
have, like, unknown authors.

00:17:59.050 --> 00:18:01.882
But there I was, on
the Johnny Carson show,

00:18:01.882 --> 00:18:02.840
at the end of the show.

00:18:02.840 --> 00:18:04.640
It was called the author's spot.

00:18:04.640 --> 00:18:07.120
And it went great.

00:18:07.120 --> 00:18:10.180
I later realized
that the reason went

00:18:10.180 --> 00:18:12.030
great-- I thought, wow,
television is easy,

00:18:12.030 --> 00:18:13.630
you know, everybody laughed.

00:18:13.630 --> 00:18:16.130
I later realized it went great
because Johnny Carson was one

00:18:16.130 --> 00:18:17.620
of the best interviewers ever.

00:18:17.620 --> 00:18:22.400
And he was masterful at
giving me the laughs.

00:18:22.400 --> 00:18:26.310
So anyway, as soon as it ended,
as soon as our seven minutes

00:18:26.310 --> 00:18:28.630
ended the band starts playing.

00:18:28.630 --> 00:18:30.380
As soon as the camera's
off, Johnny Carson

00:18:30.380 --> 00:18:31.920
lights a cigarette.

00:18:31.920 --> 00:18:33.976
And he turned to me,
and the only thing

00:18:33.976 --> 00:18:36.600
that he ever said to me, just to
me, that we weren't on the air

00:18:36.600 --> 00:18:39.070
was, I used to try
to do it yourself.

00:18:39.070 --> 00:18:39.930
Pause.

00:18:39.930 --> 00:18:42.980
You can't do shit yourself.

00:18:42.980 --> 00:18:43.890
And I laughed.

00:18:43.890 --> 00:18:44.704
And that was it.

00:18:44.704 --> 00:18:46.120
Anyway, but I
thought of that when

00:18:46.120 --> 00:18:47.245
I was writing this chapter.

00:18:47.245 --> 00:18:49.752
Because I've been a homeowner
for a long, long time.

00:18:49.752 --> 00:18:51.710
And I've owned many, many
homes over the years.

00:18:51.710 --> 00:18:53.890
And I've learned that I
cannot do anything myself.

00:18:53.890 --> 00:18:57.872
I have to hire a guy
with a truck to come.

00:18:57.872 --> 00:18:58.580
Guy with a truck.

00:18:58.580 --> 00:19:01.110
And he always comes, and
there's a certain ritual

00:19:01.110 --> 00:19:02.556
to the guy with the truck.

00:19:02.556 --> 00:19:04.180
If you are a homeowner,
I'm sure you've

00:19:04.180 --> 00:19:05.221
been through this ritual.

00:19:05.221 --> 00:19:07.847
He comes in, first he wants
to ask you some questions.

00:19:07.847 --> 00:19:09.680
Which I hate, because
if I knew the answers,

00:19:09.680 --> 00:19:11.590
I wouldn't call the
guy with the truck.

00:19:11.590 --> 00:19:14.040
But he always wants to
know something like,

00:19:14.040 --> 00:19:16.820
can you tell me where your
demodulation juncture is?

00:19:16.820 --> 00:19:19.638
It should be near the
Boolean overpass valve.

00:19:19.638 --> 00:19:21.096
And I never know
where anything is.

00:19:21.096 --> 00:19:21.770
I say, I'm sorry.

00:19:21.770 --> 00:19:23.600
I'm sitting there looking
at whatever stupid thing I'm

00:19:23.600 --> 00:19:24.910
looking at on my
computer screen, which

00:19:24.910 --> 00:19:26.118
looks like I'm doing nothing.

00:19:26.118 --> 00:19:27.495
But I'm a humor writer.

00:19:27.495 --> 00:19:29.120
If I'm looking at a
Japanese game show,

00:19:29.120 --> 00:19:30.661
there's a professional
reason for it.

00:19:30.661 --> 00:19:32.290
OK?

00:19:32.290 --> 00:19:34.010
But anyway, so he goes off.

00:19:34.010 --> 00:19:35.830
And then, the part
I hate the most

00:19:35.830 --> 00:19:39.652
is when he wants to come
and show you something.

00:19:39.652 --> 00:19:40.860
They always have to show you.

00:19:40.860 --> 00:19:41.901
Can I show you something?

00:19:41.901 --> 00:19:43.540
Mr. Barry, can I
show you something?

00:19:43.540 --> 00:19:44.610
And first of all, I
don't want to see it,

00:19:44.610 --> 00:19:45.400
because it's not
going to be good.

00:19:45.400 --> 00:19:46.750
It's never a good thing.

00:19:46.750 --> 00:19:49.640
The truck guy never
says, you see this?

00:19:49.640 --> 00:19:53.070
That's exactly the way
that's supposed to look.

00:19:53.070 --> 00:19:55.150
That's not going to
cost you a nickel.

00:19:55.150 --> 00:19:58.190
That is never what the truck
guy has to talk to you about.

00:19:58.190 --> 00:19:59.870
It's always something
very expensive,

00:19:59.870 --> 00:20:01.090
that was always done wrong.

00:20:01.090 --> 00:20:02.130
And you always want
to say, well, whoever

00:20:02.130 --> 00:20:03.300
did it wrong was in a truck.

00:20:03.300 --> 00:20:05.940
I'll tell you that, right now.

00:20:05.940 --> 00:20:09.020
So anyway, I wrote a
chapter about-- an essay

00:20:09.020 --> 00:20:11.370
about not being able
to do things yourself.

00:20:11.370 --> 00:20:12.830
Having to call the truck guy.

00:20:12.830 --> 00:20:19.309
And the big culprit in
the do-it-yourself world.

00:20:19.309 --> 00:20:21.600
The one that keeps convincing
people they can do things

00:20:21.600 --> 00:20:26.610
themselves, is like, you know,
the big-- what's the name?

00:20:26.610 --> 00:20:29.470
The big hardware store that
advertises all-- why am I'm

00:20:29.470 --> 00:20:30.525
blanking on it?

00:20:30.525 --> 00:20:30.810
AUDIENCE: Home Depot?

00:20:30.810 --> 00:20:31.768
DAVE BARRY: Home Depot.

00:20:31.768 --> 00:20:32.390
Home Depot.

00:20:32.390 --> 00:20:34.056
They run those
commercials where there's

00:20:34.056 --> 00:20:36.470
like a happy, cheerful
homeowning couple.

00:20:36.470 --> 00:20:39.110
One minute they're in the Home
Depot store looking at tiles.

00:20:39.110 --> 00:20:39.800
You know?

00:20:39.800 --> 00:20:41.492
And then they show
like one second

00:20:41.492 --> 00:20:43.950
of them wearing goggles and
drilling something, or screwing

00:20:43.950 --> 00:20:44.950
a screw in.

00:20:44.950 --> 00:20:48.500
And then there's a
whole new kitchen.

00:20:48.500 --> 00:20:52.380
Which is a very misleading
view of do-it-yourself.

00:20:52.380 --> 00:20:56.760
So I propose, in
my book, a new kind

00:20:56.760 --> 00:21:01.550
of hardware store called
Reality Based Hardware.

00:21:01.550 --> 00:21:04.630
It would be a hardware
store where if you went in,

00:21:04.630 --> 00:21:06.730
we have specially trained
representatives there.

00:21:06.730 --> 00:21:08.420
If you went in,
they would actively

00:21:08.420 --> 00:21:10.220
try to discourage
you from whatever

00:21:10.220 --> 00:21:11.920
it is you were trying to do.

00:21:11.920 --> 00:21:14.910
So I have a little
dialogue here,

00:21:14.910 --> 00:21:16.400
between a homeowner
and an employee

00:21:16.400 --> 00:21:17.830
of Reality Based Hardware.

00:21:17.830 --> 00:21:20.760
Homeowner, I want to
install a ceiling fan.

00:21:20.760 --> 00:21:23.300
Employee, Really?

00:21:23.300 --> 00:21:24.740
Homeowner, Yes.

00:21:24.740 --> 00:21:27.592
Employee, You want to install a
machine with long, sharp blades

00:21:27.592 --> 00:21:29.550
whirling at high speeds
directly over the heads

00:21:29.550 --> 00:21:31.730
of live human beings?

00:21:31.730 --> 00:21:33.970
Homeowner, Well, yes.

00:21:33.970 --> 00:21:35.630
Employee, I see.

00:21:35.630 --> 00:21:37.950
And do you have any particular
expertise in this area?

00:21:37.950 --> 00:21:40.720
Any training in the field
the ceiling fan installation?

00:21:40.720 --> 00:21:45.170
Homeowner, Um, no, not in
ceiling fan insulation, per se.

00:21:45.170 --> 00:21:47.870
Employee, In what, then?

00:21:47.870 --> 00:21:50.870
Homeowner, I'm a dentist.

00:21:50.870 --> 00:21:51.772
Employee, I see.

00:21:51.772 --> 00:21:54.230
And would you comfortable having
a professional ceiling fan

00:21:54.230 --> 00:21:57.477
installer give you a root canal?

00:21:57.477 --> 00:21:59.310
Homeowner, Well, no,
but that's a different.

00:21:59.310 --> 00:22:01.120
Employee, I'd like
you to take a look

00:22:01.120 --> 00:22:04.950
at this photograph of a recent,
quote, do-it-yourself ceiling

00:22:04.950 --> 00:22:07.510
fan installation.

00:22:07.510 --> 00:22:09.490
Homeowner, My god, is that?

00:22:09.490 --> 00:22:10.675
Employee, Yes.

00:22:10.675 --> 00:22:11.175
His hand.

00:22:13.880 --> 00:22:15.210
It landed eight feet away.

00:22:18.460 --> 00:22:22.640
I have an essay in
here about Russia.

00:22:22.640 --> 00:22:24.960
I went to Russia last
fall, with a friend

00:22:24.960 --> 00:22:27.780
of mine named Ridley Pearson,
the co-author of some books I

00:22:27.780 --> 00:22:28.770
wrote.

00:22:28.770 --> 00:22:30.680
We went for the US
State Department

00:22:30.680 --> 00:22:34.030
to Russia, as part of a
program to improve relations

00:22:34.030 --> 00:22:35.050
between the two nations.

00:22:35.050 --> 00:22:38.920
So you see how
that's working out.

00:22:38.920 --> 00:22:40.530
So anyway, I wrote
an essay about it.

00:22:40.530 --> 00:22:42.500
You won't really learn
a lot about Russia,

00:22:42.500 --> 00:22:44.810
because I never understood
what anybody was saying.

00:22:44.810 --> 00:22:47.970
But I had a pretty good
time, except for-- I

00:22:47.970 --> 00:22:49.500
ate Mexican food.

00:22:49.500 --> 00:22:51.420
I ate a chimichanga.

00:22:51.420 --> 00:22:52.210
This is true.

00:22:52.210 --> 00:22:54.250
It's like, amazing, how
many non-Russian foods

00:22:54.250 --> 00:22:55.430
you can get in Moscow.

00:22:55.430 --> 00:22:59.555
And I developed a case of
global thermonuclear diarrhea.

00:23:02.270 --> 00:23:04.770
I guess my main piece of
advice is, if you go to Russia,

00:23:04.770 --> 00:23:07.492
don't eat the Mexican food.

00:23:07.492 --> 00:23:08.950
Just like a weaponized
chimichanga.

00:23:11.930 --> 00:23:16.000
And I close the book with
a letter to my grandson.

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:19.900
I became a grandfather last May.

00:23:19.900 --> 00:23:23.880
I really, I get no
credit for that.

00:23:23.880 --> 00:23:25.896
My son Rob, he actually
works here in New York.

00:23:25.896 --> 00:23:27.520
He works for "The
Wall Street Journal."

00:23:27.520 --> 00:23:30.200
But he-- well, actually
his wife had the baby.

00:23:30.200 --> 00:23:32.960
I'll be technical here.

00:23:32.960 --> 00:23:37.900
And I wanted to write a letter
to him, passing on the wisdom

00:23:37.900 --> 00:23:38.650
that I've learned.

00:23:38.650 --> 00:23:40.190
It was an interesting thing.

00:23:40.190 --> 00:23:41.821
You know, I kind
of envision what

00:23:41.821 --> 00:23:44.070
it would be like to be like
to be a grandson-- I would

00:23:44.070 --> 00:23:45.653
be a grandfather--
it didn't start out

00:23:45.653 --> 00:23:47.080
the way I pictured it.

00:23:47.080 --> 00:23:50.650
My daughter-in-law is
Jewish, and so they

00:23:50.650 --> 00:23:53.080
decided to have a Briss.

00:23:53.080 --> 00:23:57.890
I don't know if you're familiar
with the Briss, but basically--

00:23:57.890 --> 00:24:00.220
and I want to stress before
I start, I love Judaism.

00:24:00.220 --> 00:24:01.080
My wife is Jewish.

00:24:01.080 --> 00:24:02.627
She's Cuban Jewish.

00:24:02.627 --> 00:24:04.210
My joke is, they
didn't come on rafts,

00:24:04.210 --> 00:24:07.485
they parted of the Caribbean.

00:24:07.485 --> 00:24:08.282
So I love Judaism.

00:24:08.282 --> 00:24:09.990
It's a great religion,
except for I'm not

00:24:09.990 --> 00:24:12.600
so big on the Briss concept.

00:24:12.600 --> 00:24:14.540
The way it works is,
it's a tradition,

00:24:14.540 --> 00:24:17.350
that when the baby is
born, on the eighth day

00:24:17.350 --> 00:24:20.250
the baby has to be
circumcised, and then there

00:24:20.250 --> 00:24:23.110
are deli platters.

00:24:23.110 --> 00:24:25.860
Sometimes on the same surface.

00:24:25.860 --> 00:24:30.890
And I looked-- when
I found I was going

00:24:30.890 --> 00:24:33.149
to be involved in
this Briss, I looked

00:24:33.149 --> 00:24:35.440
in the Bible-- which is
online, you'll be glad to know.

00:24:39.270 --> 00:24:42.920
The way it came about, the
story is, in the Bible,

00:24:42.920 --> 00:24:45.850
there's a whole explanation
why Jews do this.

00:24:45.850 --> 00:24:49.790
Abraham, he's 99
years old, Abraham.

00:24:49.790 --> 00:24:52.850
He's like the
patriarch of-- and God

00:24:52.850 --> 00:24:55.700
comes to see him, which is
never a good thing in the Bible.

00:24:55.700 --> 00:24:57.450
It's kind of like when
the truck guy wants

00:24:57.450 --> 00:24:59.580
to show you something.

00:24:59.580 --> 00:25:02.200
God never comes to say, hey,
I just turned all of Lake Erie

00:25:02.200 --> 00:25:02.810
into beer.

00:25:02.810 --> 00:25:05.520
Come on.

00:25:05.520 --> 00:25:06.920
Never anything great like that.

00:25:06.920 --> 00:25:09.564
It's always something like,
you're going to smite somebody,

00:25:09.564 --> 00:25:10.980
you're going to
have to sacrifice,

00:25:10.980 --> 00:25:12.938
you're going to have to
build something out of,

00:25:12.938 --> 00:25:15.114
you know, goat skins, whatever.

00:25:15.114 --> 00:25:17.530
God has got something in his
mind, some bee in his bonnet.

00:25:17.530 --> 00:25:20.170
In this case, God
tells Abraham, I'm

00:25:20.170 --> 00:25:27.270
going to make you-- you're going
to be the patriarch-- you're

00:25:27.270 --> 00:25:29.582
going to be the forefather
of all these kings.

00:25:29.582 --> 00:25:31.290
I'm going to give you
the land of Cannan.

00:25:31.290 --> 00:25:35.030
Cannan is the biblical word
for what is now Long Island.

00:25:38.980 --> 00:25:42.157
But he said, we have to have
a token of our covenant,

00:25:42.157 --> 00:25:43.615
is you have to
circumcise yourself.

00:25:43.615 --> 00:25:45.573
I'm not kidding, It's
right there in the Bible.

00:25:45.573 --> 00:25:48.760
He's telling a
99-year-old man that he

00:25:48.760 --> 00:25:51.160
has to circumcise himself.

00:25:51.160 --> 00:25:54.921
And you think, like, why
would that be the token?

00:25:54.921 --> 00:25:55.420
You know?

00:25:55.420 --> 00:25:56.753
Why can't they just shake hands?

00:25:59.290 --> 00:26:05.747
And speaking of shaking
hands, not only has Abraham

00:26:05.747 --> 00:26:07.580
got to circumcise
himself, but God tells him

00:26:07.580 --> 00:26:09.380
he has to circumcise
everybody in his household.

00:26:09.380 --> 00:26:10.970
How would you like to
be in that household?

00:26:10.970 --> 00:26:12.560
Hey, guess what
God told me to do.

00:26:12.560 --> 00:26:14.690
You know?

00:26:14.690 --> 00:26:20.703
So anyway, my
grandson had a Briss.

00:26:20.703 --> 00:26:22.536
And I was chosen-- I
was given the honor-- I

00:26:22.536 --> 00:26:25.420
was told it was an honor--
of being the Sandek, which

00:26:25.420 --> 00:26:28.550
is the person who
holds the baby's legs.

00:26:28.550 --> 00:26:33.260
While the Mohel-- which is
a Hebrew word for snipper--

00:26:33.260 --> 00:26:35.970
performs the actual
circumcision.

00:26:35.970 --> 00:26:39.454
That was my first real
interaction with my grandson.

00:26:39.454 --> 00:26:41.370
Holding his legs while
he's being circumcised.

00:26:41.370 --> 00:26:43.495
And I, you know, I pictured
something like fishing.

00:26:43.495 --> 00:26:45.414
You know?

00:26:45.414 --> 00:26:47.080
Or learning to
skateboard, or something.

00:26:47.080 --> 00:26:49.480
But no-- so I'm
just kind of hoping

00:26:49.480 --> 00:26:51.760
he's forgotten all about that.

00:26:51.760 --> 00:26:54.740
But anyway, this
leads me to the one

00:26:54.740 --> 00:26:56.180
I've been scared to talk about.

00:26:56.180 --> 00:26:59.670
There's one other topic I wrote
an essay about in this book,

00:26:59.670 --> 00:27:00.355
Google Glass.

00:27:04.490 --> 00:27:07.480
And I bought a pair.

00:27:07.480 --> 00:27:09.620
With my own money, I bought.

00:27:09.620 --> 00:27:11.340
I became-- they
call it an explorer.

00:27:11.340 --> 00:27:12.756
Is anybody here--
no, I don't even

00:27:12.756 --> 00:27:15.650
want to know if anybody here
is from the Google Glass.

00:27:15.650 --> 00:27:18.044
And I wrote about Google Glass.

00:27:18.044 --> 00:27:19.960
So I was going to read
you a little bit of it,

00:27:19.960 --> 00:27:21.600
and you'll see where
I'm coming from.

00:27:21.600 --> 00:27:24.390
And then you can
throw stuff at me.

00:27:24.390 --> 00:27:26.304
Before you read this
review of Google Glass,

00:27:26.304 --> 00:27:27.720
I want to stress
that I am totally

00:27:27.720 --> 00:27:29.830
down with modern technology.

00:27:29.830 --> 00:27:32.310
I'm not some clueless old
fart shouting hello, hello

00:27:32.310 --> 00:27:34.890
into a mobile phone he
is holding upside down.

00:27:34.890 --> 00:27:37.660
Although I have done that.

00:27:37.660 --> 00:27:38.930
I love new technology.

00:27:38.930 --> 00:27:40.950
I am what is known
as an early adopter.

00:27:40.950 --> 00:27:42.510
Over the decades,
I have spent 10s

00:27:42.510 --> 00:27:45.340
of thousands of dollars
adopting new technology that I

00:27:45.340 --> 00:27:47.390
use for periods of time
ranging from one week

00:27:47.390 --> 00:27:48.880
to as long as three weeks.

00:27:48.880 --> 00:27:50.420
At which time it
ceased to be as new

00:27:50.420 --> 00:27:52.430
as it once was, leaving
me with no choice

00:27:52.430 --> 00:27:53.860
but to buy a newer one.

00:27:53.860 --> 00:27:57.320
I have boxes and boxes filled
with old new technology.

00:27:57.320 --> 00:27:59.860
And still more boxes
containing dense tangled snarls

00:27:59.860 --> 00:28:02.170
of cables and power
adapters, that I

00:28:02.170 --> 00:28:05.010
would need if I ever wanted to
make the technology work again.

00:28:05.010 --> 00:28:08.000
Which, of course, I never
would, because it is old.

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:10.390
I have been buying GPS
units since the days when

00:28:10.390 --> 00:28:12.940
they had tiny black and
white screens, and said only,

00:28:12.940 --> 00:28:15.250
you are probably in either
North or South America.

00:28:18.660 --> 00:28:21.830
I have owned mobile phones
the size of LeBron James.

00:28:21.830 --> 00:28:24.040
I early adopted
every single version

00:28:24.040 --> 00:28:25.990
of the Windows operating
system, including

00:28:25.990 --> 00:28:28.180
Vista, which summoned
hell demons who

00:28:28.180 --> 00:28:30.070
possessed your computer
and played pranks,

00:28:30.070 --> 00:28:32.480
such as changing all
your verbs to adjectives.

00:28:32.480 --> 00:28:35.260
And I continued early adopting
Windows versions after that.

00:28:35.260 --> 00:28:37.680
If Windows came out with a
version called Windows Stab You

00:28:37.680 --> 00:28:41.600
in the Eyeball With a
Fork, I would adopt it.

00:28:41.600 --> 00:28:45.300
And I skip over the point where
own like 11 electric guitars.

00:28:45.300 --> 00:28:48.130
Now the point is, I consider
myself to be pro technology,

00:28:48.130 --> 00:28:49.940
and knowledgeable about gadgets.

00:28:49.940 --> 00:28:52.640
So when I heard about
Google Glass, I wanted it.

00:28:52.640 --> 00:28:55.780
I wasn't sure exactly what it
did, it but I knew it was new

00:28:55.780 --> 00:28:58.670
and it apparently
involved electricity.

00:28:58.670 --> 00:29:01.450
It also involved Google,
of which I am a huge fan.

00:29:01.450 --> 00:29:02.860
And this is true, I am.

00:29:02.860 --> 00:29:04.920
Google has basically
replaced my brain.

00:29:07.740 --> 00:29:09.115
That's also
basically the-- there

00:29:09.115 --> 00:29:11.156
was a time when, if somebody
asked me a question,

00:29:11.156 --> 00:29:12.680
say, who is Socrates?

00:29:12.680 --> 00:29:14.600
I had to manually
think about it.

00:29:14.600 --> 00:29:17.050
Whereas now I just Google it,
and boom, I have the answer.

00:29:17.050 --> 00:29:20.760
Quote, an ancient dead person.

00:29:20.760 --> 00:29:22.510
Google makes thinking
so much easier.

00:29:22.510 --> 00:29:24.510
If Google had existed
when I was in college,

00:29:24.510 --> 00:29:26.240
I would have spent
the entire four

00:29:26.240 --> 00:29:28.810
years getting high and
listening to Moby Grape,

00:29:28.810 --> 00:29:33.450
instead of just 87% of the time.

00:29:33.450 --> 00:29:34.980
So anyway, I got Google Glass.

00:29:34.980 --> 00:29:37.360
It cost $1,500, which
sounds like a lot of money,

00:29:37.360 --> 00:29:40.200
until you realize that it's
100% tax deductible if you

00:29:40.200 --> 00:29:41.450
write about it in this book.

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:49.140
What is Google Glass?

00:29:49.140 --> 00:29:50.790
Its a lightweight
electronic device,

00:29:50.790 --> 00:29:54.130
sort of like a high-tech looking
eyeglass frame without lenses

00:29:54.130 --> 00:29:55.510
but you wear on your head.

00:29:55.510 --> 00:29:57.200
On the front right
side of the device

00:29:57.200 --> 00:29:59.130
is a tiny camera and
a miniature screen,

00:29:59.130 --> 00:30:01.729
that you can theoretically
see with your right eye.

00:30:01.729 --> 00:30:03.520
There's also a tiny
microphone and speaker.

00:30:03.520 --> 00:30:05.103
It connects wirelessly
to the internet

00:30:05.103 --> 00:30:06.650
through Wi-Fi or
a Bluetooth phone.

00:30:06.650 --> 00:30:09.080
So basically, when you
put on Google Glass,

00:30:09.080 --> 00:30:12.310
you're wearing a tiny hands-free
computer with direct access

00:30:12.310 --> 00:30:14.030
to the unimaginably
vast information

00:30:14.030 --> 00:30:16.010
resources of the internet.

00:30:16.010 --> 00:30:18.810
Think for a moment
about what this means.

00:30:18.810 --> 00:30:22.920
It means you look
like a douche bag.

00:30:22.920 --> 00:30:23.700
So anyway.

00:30:28.300 --> 00:30:29.200
Seriously, you do.

00:30:29.200 --> 00:30:30.450
There is no getting around it.

00:30:30.450 --> 00:30:33.060
My daughter-- who has been my
daughter for her entire life,

00:30:33.060 --> 00:30:35.500
and therefore has developed
a very high tolerance

00:30:35.500 --> 00:30:37.276
for being embarrassed
by me-- refused

00:30:37.276 --> 00:30:38.650
to walk into a
restaurant with me

00:30:38.650 --> 00:30:40.940
until I removed my Google Glass.

00:30:40.940 --> 00:30:43.430
If you go to the official
Google website for Google Glass,

00:30:43.430 --> 00:30:45.680
you will see photos of
attractive young people wearing

00:30:45.680 --> 00:30:47.630
Google Glass as they
engage in a variety

00:30:47.630 --> 00:30:49.010
of modern youthful activities.

00:30:49.010 --> 00:30:50.810
Biking, running,
golfing, chopping

00:30:50.810 --> 00:30:53.260
organic vegetables, et cetera.

00:30:53.260 --> 00:30:55.750
Google has enough money
to buy whatever it wants.

00:30:55.750 --> 00:30:57.930
Asia, for example.

00:30:57.930 --> 00:31:00.670
So you know they paid the
for the absolute best looking

00:31:00.670 --> 00:31:02.900
photos of the absolute
best looking Glass wearing

00:31:02.900 --> 00:31:04.480
individuals money could buy.

00:31:04.480 --> 00:31:07.670
They still look
like douche bags.

00:31:07.670 --> 00:31:09.890
So anyway, that's--
and I'll be honest,

00:31:09.890 --> 00:31:11.940
I don't give Google
Glass a great review.

00:31:11.940 --> 00:31:13.890
It's probably because
I'm 67 years old,

00:31:13.890 --> 00:31:16.500
and I could never
really see the thing.

00:31:16.500 --> 00:31:17.390
But I wore them.

00:31:17.390 --> 00:31:18.390
Wore them for a weekend.

00:31:18.390 --> 00:31:19.920
I went to wedding with them.

00:31:19.920 --> 00:31:23.350
I was very popular
with other guests.

00:31:23.350 --> 00:31:25.120
And then I did close it.

00:31:25.120 --> 00:31:28.740
I know that you've discontinued,
for now, the current version,

00:31:28.740 --> 00:31:30.096
and looking at improvements.

00:31:30.096 --> 00:31:31.470
And I proposed
some improvements.

00:31:31.470 --> 00:31:36.060
And one of them would be,
like an invisibility cloak.

00:31:36.060 --> 00:31:38.770
But, you know, when the next
one comes out, I'll buy it.

00:31:38.770 --> 00:31:41.690
Because that's the kind
of early adopter I am.

00:31:41.690 --> 00:31:44.910
So anyway, that's the
Google part of my book.

00:31:44.910 --> 00:31:46.740
So, I don't how
long I've gone on.

00:31:46.740 --> 00:31:50.380
They told me there was a
timer, but I can't find it.

00:31:50.380 --> 00:31:53.860
So I would be happy
to take questions

00:31:53.860 --> 00:31:58.410
on anything, except anything
that requires knowledge.

00:31:58.410 --> 00:31:59.440
I'm not good at that.

00:31:59.440 --> 00:32:00.980
That's why I became
humor writer.

00:32:00.980 --> 00:32:01.479
Yeah?

