I move to Florida.

00:33:52.190 --> 00:33:54.540
DAVE BARRY: Come on
down to Florida, yeah.

00:33:54.540 --> 00:33:56.480
What a lot of seniors
like to do is-- just

00:33:56.480 --> 00:33:58.850
to make sure they have enough
mass-- get two Oldsmobiles

00:33:58.850 --> 00:34:00.872
and have them welded together.

00:34:00.872 --> 00:34:03.361
Get that big mass around you.

00:34:03.361 --> 00:34:05.610
AUDIENCE: But listen, a
question, not about your book,

00:34:05.610 --> 00:34:07.693
but about something that
happened a long time ago,

00:34:07.693 --> 00:34:10.429
long before Sophie was born.

00:34:10.429 --> 00:34:12.520
Back in the late
'80s, early '90s,

00:34:12.520 --> 00:34:14.409
I think you were
one of the first,

00:34:14.409 --> 00:34:17.179
if not the first, sort
of mainstream author that

00:34:17.179 --> 00:34:19.969
was regularly syndicated
on the network.

00:34:19.969 --> 00:34:23.190
On the internet,
ARPANET at that time.

00:34:23.190 --> 00:34:28.800
And I think it wasn't with
your authorization, at least

00:34:28.800 --> 00:34:29.780
initially.

00:34:29.780 --> 00:34:31.530
It was just people
were taking your stuff.

00:34:31.530 --> 00:34:34.070
We had a mailing
list for awhile.

00:34:34.070 --> 00:34:35.850
I think that Brad
Templeton picked you up

00:34:35.850 --> 00:34:40.400
on ClariNet as one of the first
syndicated authors, and such.

00:34:40.400 --> 00:34:42.760
Can you talk a
little bit about what

00:34:42.760 --> 00:34:46.520
it was like to be an author
and suddenly discover

00:34:46.520 --> 00:34:50.110
that, totally separate
from what you thought

00:34:50.110 --> 00:34:51.580
was your syndication
pattern, there

00:34:51.580 --> 00:34:54.050
was this bunch of geeks
on the internet that

00:34:54.050 --> 00:34:55.449
were syndicating your stuff.

00:34:55.449 --> 00:34:56.909
How did react to that?

00:34:56.909 --> 00:34:58.870
And has it made any
difference in your career

00:34:58.870 --> 00:35:02.970
to have been one of the first
internet syndicated authors?

00:35:02.970 --> 00:35:04.740
DAVE BARRY: I do
remember it quite well.

00:35:04.740 --> 00:35:08.700
And it took me a while to
figure out what was happening.

00:35:08.700 --> 00:35:11.356
But people wrote-- back then
we had letters-- and some

00:35:11.356 --> 00:35:13.855
sometimes they would write me
letters and send me printouts,

00:35:13.855 --> 00:35:16.460
and said, you realize
you're on this?

00:35:16.460 --> 00:35:18.240
And I thought it was cool.

00:35:18.240 --> 00:35:22.720
What's funny about it-- I
have about nine thoughts

00:35:22.720 --> 00:35:25.120
trying to come out once,
so I'll try to pick one.

00:35:25.120 --> 00:35:27.580
What was really funny about
it is if the newspaper

00:35:27.580 --> 00:35:31.810
business had had any
brains back then,

00:35:31.810 --> 00:35:35.160
they would have seen something
that they never did see.

00:35:35.160 --> 00:35:38.670
And now the newspaper businesses
is going out of business

00:35:38.670 --> 00:35:40.230
because it's run
by English majors.

00:35:45.390 --> 00:35:47.475
But I thought, well this
is really interesting,

00:35:47.475 --> 00:35:48.850
that all these
people-- you know,

00:35:48.850 --> 00:35:51.140
it didn't occur to me to
look at it financially,

00:35:51.140 --> 00:35:52.750
because it wouldn't have made
any difference to me anyway.

00:35:52.750 --> 00:35:55.190
You know, I was already in
whatever papers I was in.

00:35:55.190 --> 00:35:57.065
And I don't think it
was taking anything away

00:35:57.065 --> 00:36:02.524
from my way of making a living.

00:36:02.524 --> 00:36:04.940
And I just figured, well those
people will also buy books,

00:36:04.940 --> 00:36:05.773
and stuff like that.

00:36:05.773 --> 00:36:07.500
So I thought that it was great.

00:36:07.500 --> 00:36:10.320
I do remember the "Miami
Herald" and Knight Ridder

00:36:10.320 --> 00:36:12.580
going way out of their
way to try to stop it.

00:36:12.580 --> 00:36:15.240
And failing utterly.

00:36:15.240 --> 00:36:17.560
Again, English majors
versus people who actually

00:36:17.560 --> 00:36:18.560
understood the internet.

00:36:21.269 --> 00:36:23.810
So I just sort of remember it
as kind of an interesting time.

00:36:23.810 --> 00:36:25.430
And that's all gone, right?

00:36:25.430 --> 00:36:28.686
Those mailing lists,
whatever those?

00:36:28.686 --> 00:36:30.682
AUDIENCE: They're
still there, they just

00:36:30.682 --> 00:36:32.678
don't get-- they're
not-- in fact,

00:36:32.678 --> 00:36:35.672
they probably have more people
on them than they did then.

00:36:35.672 --> 00:36:38.666
But it's a much tinier
percentage of the world

00:36:38.666 --> 00:36:40.180
than it was then.

00:36:40.180 --> 00:36:42.620
DAVE BARRY: At some
point, I got involved--

00:36:42.620 --> 00:36:44.910
I was able to
actually post onto it,

00:36:44.910 --> 00:36:47.040
or whatever the word would be.

00:36:47.040 --> 00:36:49.110
And what I do
remember, was after one

00:36:49.110 --> 00:36:51.110
really long drunken
night in London--

00:36:51.110 --> 00:36:54.030
I was on a book tour in London
with a very funny newspaper

00:36:54.030 --> 00:36:55.130
columnist over there.

00:36:55.130 --> 00:36:58.450
And I wrote him a really
ridiculously obscene email

00:36:58.450 --> 00:37:01.260
at the end of the
evening, thanking him.

00:37:01.260 --> 00:37:04.950
And using the term
Mr. Chuckle Trousers,

00:37:04.950 --> 00:37:07.080
which had great
significance that night.

00:37:09.600 --> 00:37:12.060
And instead of
going just to him,

00:37:12.060 --> 00:37:17.360
it went to everybody
in the world.

00:37:17.360 --> 00:37:19.310
So that was my other
big lesson about that.

00:37:22.180 --> 00:37:22.680
Yeah?

00:37:22.680 --> 00:37:24.160
AUDIENCE: Dave,
thanks for coming.

00:37:24.160 --> 00:37:24.820
DAVE BARRY: Thank you.

00:37:24.820 --> 00:37:26.445
AUDIENCE: So I have
a couple questions.

00:37:26.445 --> 00:37:27.870
DAVE BARRY: What kind?

00:37:27.870 --> 00:37:29.230
AUDIENCE: A couple questions.

00:37:29.230 --> 00:37:30.855
First of all, my
parents live in Miami,

00:37:30.855 --> 00:37:32.730
so I've been looking at
your stuff for years.

00:37:32.730 --> 00:37:34.670
DAVE BARRY: Everyone's
parents live in Miami.

00:37:34.670 --> 00:37:36.545
AUDIENCE: But we came
from South America, so.

00:37:36.545 --> 00:37:37.300
DAVE BARRY: OK.

00:37:37.300 --> 00:37:37.785
AUDIENCE: From Columbia.

00:37:37.785 --> 00:37:38.850
DAVE BARRY: Columbia!

00:37:38.850 --> 00:37:40.106
AUDIENCE: No threat.

00:37:40.106 --> 00:37:42.400
DAVE BARRY: No, I have
many Colombian friends.

00:37:42.400 --> 00:37:44.227
AUDIENCE: So first
question is, what--

00:37:44.227 --> 00:37:46.310
DAVE BARRY: Can I tell you
the first Colombian guy

00:37:46.310 --> 00:37:47.927
I met in Miami?

00:37:47.927 --> 00:37:49.510
I know I'm interrupting
your question,

00:37:49.510 --> 00:37:54.110
but-- This was in the '80s, when
there were a lot of Colombians

00:37:54.110 --> 00:37:55.450
there for the wrong reasons.

00:37:55.450 --> 00:37:57.241
You know, they were
not software engineers.

00:37:59.640 --> 00:38:04.530
And I was meeting, as it
happened, a police officer

00:38:04.530 --> 00:38:06.400
in a bar in South Beach.

00:38:06.400 --> 00:38:07.590
And he had not arrived yet.

00:38:07.590 --> 00:38:09.340
And it was not like a
close friend police,

00:38:09.340 --> 00:38:10.550
it was a guy-- I
was doing a column,

00:38:10.550 --> 00:38:11.966
and he was going
to meet be there.

00:38:11.966 --> 00:38:14.367
So I'm sitting there, and
this guy comes over to me,

00:38:14.367 --> 00:38:15.700
and he goes, are you Dave Barry?

00:38:15.700 --> 00:38:16.650
And I go, yeah, I am.

00:38:16.650 --> 00:38:17.430
And he sits down.

00:38:17.430 --> 00:38:18.180
He's a nice guy.

00:38:18.180 --> 00:38:21.570
We're chatting away.

00:38:21.570 --> 00:38:23.374
After a while I said,
well, what do you do?

00:38:23.374 --> 00:38:26.040
And he goes, I'll be honest with
you, I'm a narcotics trafficer.

00:38:31.290 --> 00:38:33.580
I said well, do
you mind if like we

00:38:33.580 --> 00:38:37.275
carry on this conversation
in, like, another state?

00:38:37.275 --> 00:38:39.400
But the other one, the
other Colombian thing-- it's

00:38:39.400 --> 00:38:41.440
actually in this book.

00:38:41.440 --> 00:38:45.250
In the Uruguay Columbia game
at the World Cup this-- yes,

00:38:45.250 --> 00:38:47.570
I sat in the Colombian
rooting section.

00:38:47.570 --> 00:38:49.090
And we actually rooted for them.

00:38:49.090 --> 00:38:50.360
But I sat with a
bunch of Colombians.

00:38:50.360 --> 00:38:51.080
And they said,
where are you from?

00:38:51.080 --> 00:38:51.430
And I said, Miami.

00:38:51.430 --> 00:38:52.630
He said that's the
same as Colombia.

00:38:52.630 --> 00:38:53.910
Which is really kind of true.

00:38:53.910 --> 00:38:55.879
And they won that game,
as you may recall.

00:38:55.879 --> 00:38:56.670
It was a good game.

00:38:56.670 --> 00:38:59.260
But anyway, go ahead.

00:38:59.260 --> 00:39:01.545
And can you do the dance
that your team does?

00:39:01.545 --> 00:39:02.670
AUDIENCE: I'm not going to.

00:39:02.670 --> 00:39:04.730
DAVE BARRY: OK.

00:39:04.730 --> 00:39:07.150
AUDIENCE: My first
question is, what

00:39:07.150 --> 00:39:09.890
prompted you to move to
Miami in the first place?

00:39:09.890 --> 00:39:10.910
DAVE BARRY: OK, you want
me to answer that first?

00:39:10.910 --> 00:39:11.300
AUDIENCE: Yup.

00:39:11.300 --> 00:39:12.850
DAVE BARRY: Good, then I
don't have to remember it.

00:39:12.850 --> 00:39:14.420
The "Miami Herald" hired me.

00:39:14.420 --> 00:39:17.900
And for reasons of-- incredibly
poor planning on their part--

00:39:17.900 --> 00:39:20.200
they located the "Miami
Herald" in Miami.

00:39:20.200 --> 00:39:24.040
Rather than an English
speaking country or city.

00:39:24.040 --> 00:39:24.876
But anyway, no.

00:39:24.876 --> 00:39:26.660
The "Herald" hired
me, and at first I

00:39:26.660 --> 00:39:28.410
didn't want to move there.

00:39:28.410 --> 00:39:30.860
I lived in suburban
Philadelphia at the time.

00:39:30.860 --> 00:39:34.960
In lovely little quiet suburban,
not even really suburban,

00:39:34.960 --> 00:39:38.620
more like a forested place.

00:39:38.620 --> 00:39:40.530
And I went to Miami,
and I said, my god, I'm

00:39:40.530 --> 00:39:42.140
never going to move down here.

00:39:42.140 --> 00:39:43.515
And they said,
you don't have to.

00:39:43.515 --> 00:39:45.720
You can stay in Miami and
be our humor columnist.

00:39:45.720 --> 00:39:47.435
I mean stay in Glen
Mills, Pennsylvania

00:39:47.435 --> 00:39:48.560
and be our humor columnist.

00:39:48.560 --> 00:39:52.694
So I, for three years,
was the humor columnist

00:39:52.694 --> 00:39:54.110
for the "Miami
Herald," but living

00:39:54.110 --> 00:39:55.980
in suburban Philadelphia.

00:39:55.980 --> 00:39:57.890
And during those
three years, I kept

00:39:57.890 --> 00:40:00.580
visiting-- to do
stories and whatever--

00:40:00.580 --> 00:40:02.490
and I came to love Miami.

00:40:02.490 --> 00:40:03.950
And I really love it now.

00:40:03.950 --> 00:40:05.860
I would never live
anywhere else.

00:40:05.860 --> 00:40:08.820
I mean, it is, as you know,
it's a completely insane city,

00:40:08.820 --> 00:40:10.700
but it's a really
interesting, fun city.

00:40:10.700 --> 00:40:14.738
And it doesn't look like
that out there, now, there.

00:40:14.738 --> 00:40:15.404
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:40:15.404 --> 00:40:16.380
Absolutely.

00:40:16.380 --> 00:40:18.510
So my second question's
sort of related to that.

00:40:18.510 --> 00:40:20.570
Do you think your
career would have

00:40:20.570 --> 00:40:23.610
been very different had you
not had the craziness of Miami?

00:40:23.610 --> 00:40:25.110
DAVE BARRY: Yeah,
it probably would.

00:40:25.110 --> 00:40:28.890
I mean, definitely,
probably, 60% to 70%

00:40:28.890 --> 00:40:30.790
of the material I've
had over the years

00:40:30.790 --> 00:40:32.690
has come from where I am.

00:40:32.690 --> 00:40:34.672
So, yeah it would
have been different.

00:40:34.672 --> 00:40:36.630
I mean, I still would
have been a humor writer,

00:40:36.630 --> 00:40:40.220
but I would never have known
about the kind of wild world

00:40:40.220 --> 00:40:44.270
down there, which, to
this day sort of fuels me.

00:40:44.270 --> 00:40:47.077
I feel alive when
I'm down there.

00:40:47.077 --> 00:40:49.035
If nothing else, because
of the random gunfire.

00:40:51.680 --> 00:40:52.180
No.

00:40:52.180 --> 00:40:53.220
It's not so bad.

00:40:53.220 --> 00:40:54.390
It's really not.

00:40:54.390 --> 00:40:55.630
It's not random, really.

00:40:55.630 --> 00:40:57.450
It's much more targeted
than it used to be.

00:41:00.387 --> 00:41:01.220
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:41:01.220 --> 00:41:02.637
DAVE BARRY: You're welcome.

00:41:02.637 --> 00:41:03.136
Yeah?

00:41:03.136 --> 00:41:03.677
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:41:03.677 --> 00:41:04.502
Thanks for coming.

00:41:04.502 --> 00:41:06.210
My dad and I used to
listen to your books

00:41:06.210 --> 00:41:07.780
in the car on the way to
school in the morning.

00:41:07.780 --> 00:41:09.155
DAVE BARRY: You're
trying to make

00:41:09.155 --> 00:41:11.769
me feel even older than
I already am, right?

00:41:11.769 --> 00:41:13.935
This is right after the
Civil War, you and your dad.

00:41:16.166 --> 00:41:17.790
AUDIENCE: But one of
our favorite books

00:41:17.790 --> 00:41:19.310
was "Dave Barry in Cyberspace."

00:41:19.310 --> 00:41:21.450
And I was wondering, in
the intervening years,

00:41:21.450 --> 00:41:23.470
I'm sure the internet's had
a big impact on your career,

00:41:23.470 --> 00:41:23.970
and such.

00:41:23.970 --> 00:41:26.409
So is it time to write "Dave
Barry in Cyberspace 2.0?"

00:41:26.409 --> 00:41:27.450
DAVE BARRY: I don't know.

00:41:27.450 --> 00:41:29.725
Melissa, who introduced me,
was saying the same thing.

00:41:29.725 --> 00:41:30.850
That she really liked that.

00:41:30.850 --> 00:41:33.740
See, I find that book
hideously embarrassing now.

00:41:33.740 --> 00:41:36.930
You know, everything
about it just so dated.

00:41:36.930 --> 00:41:39.510
And it moves so
fast, I don't know

00:41:39.510 --> 00:41:43.160
that I could ever write about
the internet in a book that

00:41:43.160 --> 00:41:46.129
wouldn't immediately
be so out of date.

00:41:46.129 --> 00:41:47.670
I wrote a book about
bad songs, once,

00:41:47.670 --> 00:41:49.550
it was kind of the same thing.

00:41:49.550 --> 00:41:52.770
At the time, when I wrote it,
it was like in the early '90s,

00:41:52.770 --> 00:41:55.021
and everybody was sort of
listening to the same music

00:41:55.021 --> 00:41:55.520
then.

00:41:55.520 --> 00:41:57.570
But you could never--
to write that book now.

00:41:57.570 --> 00:42:00.140
And besides, I don't even know
what bad would mean anymore,

00:42:00.140 --> 00:42:01.550
to be honest with you.

00:42:01.550 --> 00:42:05.680
No, you know, these kids today
with their rock 'n' roll.

00:42:05.680 --> 00:42:06.290
I don't know.

00:42:06.290 --> 00:42:08.140
I write, occasionally,
about the internet,

00:42:08.140 --> 00:42:08.970
it's just so much a
part of our lives,

00:42:08.970 --> 00:42:11.470
but I don't think I would ever
try to write a book about it.

00:42:11.470 --> 00:42:13.512
I don't think you can
capture it anymore.

00:42:13.512 --> 00:42:14.220
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:42:14.220 --> 00:42:15.310
DAVE BARRY: Not that
I even did then.

00:42:15.310 --> 00:42:16.105
Yeah?

00:42:16.105 --> 00:42:19.390
AUDIENCE: So I have a story to
thank you, and then a question.

00:42:19.390 --> 00:42:20.480
So, I didn't grow up here.

00:42:20.480 --> 00:42:21.313
I grew up in Israel.

00:42:21.313 --> 00:42:23.930
And when I met my
family-- my wife's family

00:42:23.930 --> 00:42:26.640
did grow up in New
York, upstate New York.

00:42:26.640 --> 00:42:28.060
And it was kind
of important to me

00:42:28.060 --> 00:42:29.559
to make a good
impression them but I

00:42:29.559 --> 00:42:32.000
had like zero cultural
reference basis.

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:34.880
So I discovered two things
that could make me, like,

00:42:34.880 --> 00:42:37.184
impress my wife's parents,
especially her father.

00:42:37.184 --> 00:42:39.350
One was reading the baseball
stats the night before,

00:42:39.350 --> 00:42:41.690
so I could quote them back
at him in the morning.

00:42:41.690 --> 00:42:44.770
But the other thing was,
my view of American culture

00:42:44.770 --> 00:42:46.329
was very much shaped
by your books.

00:42:46.329 --> 00:42:48.120
And I only had your
'80s books, so it might

00:42:48.120 --> 00:42:50.230
have been a little outdated.

00:42:50.230 --> 00:42:53.400
But it definitely made a
very favorable impression.

00:42:53.400 --> 00:42:55.324
So, who knows, I might
not be here today

00:42:55.324 --> 00:42:56.240
if it weren't for you.

00:42:56.240 --> 00:42:56.530
Thank you.

00:42:56.530 --> 00:42:57.196
DAVE BARRY: Wow!

00:42:57.196 --> 00:42:59.522
So you owe me money.

00:42:59.522 --> 00:43:01.290
AUDIENCE: What?

00:43:01.290 --> 00:43:03.085
DAVE BARRY: The way
I read that question.

00:43:06.045 --> 00:43:07.420
AUDIENCE: The
actual question is,

00:43:07.420 --> 00:43:10.870
so, the persona you
project in your books

00:43:10.870 --> 00:43:12.970
is, like obviously, a
very exaggerated version

00:43:12.970 --> 00:43:13.820
of lots of things.

00:43:13.820 --> 00:43:15.270
But I've always wondered
if, like, there's

00:43:15.270 --> 00:43:16.160
some basis in fact.

00:43:16.160 --> 00:43:18.201
For example, when you
describe how you go and buy

00:43:18.201 --> 00:43:21.040
a car by sitting at the Dairy
Queen opposite, and so on.

00:43:21.040 --> 00:43:23.840
You can see that I'm
reading your old books.

00:43:23.840 --> 00:43:28.370
Is that, like, an exaggeration
of something that happened,

00:43:28.370 --> 00:43:30.929
or is it just totally unrelated
to your actual persona?

00:43:30.929 --> 00:43:31.720
DAVE BARRY: No, no.

00:43:31.720 --> 00:43:35.270
I mean, I don't run around
the house making jokes.

00:43:35.270 --> 00:43:37.780
And I compare it to, like,
if you lived with a magician,

00:43:37.780 --> 00:43:40.740
and all day long he was
pulling coins out of your ears,

00:43:40.740 --> 00:43:42.130
you would hate him.

00:43:42.130 --> 00:43:43.790
So I think I'm a normal person.

00:43:43.790 --> 00:43:48.550
But yes, most humor comes
from something real.

00:43:48.550 --> 00:43:50.940
I've always said that what
people laugh the hardest at

00:43:50.940 --> 00:43:54.394
is not something that nobody
would have thought of before,

00:43:54.394 --> 00:43:56.060
but it's something
that everyone already

00:43:56.060 --> 00:43:57.696
does sort of think
on some level,

00:43:57.696 --> 00:43:59.320
and you've just
pointed it out to them.

00:43:59.320 --> 00:44:01.620
That's when people
really laugh the hardest.

00:44:01.620 --> 00:44:03.874
So generally, I never
think in terms of,

00:44:03.874 --> 00:44:05.040
like, I'm going to use this.

00:44:05.040 --> 00:44:06.100
I'm going to use
this for material.

00:44:06.100 --> 00:44:07.016
I'm going to use this.

00:44:07.016 --> 00:44:11.231
Just sort of living a life,
material will come to you.

00:44:11.231 --> 00:44:11.730
Anyway.

00:44:11.730 --> 00:44:15.430
By the way, I went to
Israel the year before last.

00:44:15.430 --> 00:44:17.600
With my temple, which I
belong to, because-- like,

00:44:17.600 --> 00:44:20.990
there's orthodox, conservative,
reformed-- mine is relaxed.

00:44:20.990 --> 00:44:22.800
They'll let anybody in.

00:44:22.800 --> 00:44:25.580
So I belong to it, even
though I'm not Jewish.

00:44:25.580 --> 00:44:28.760
And I loved Israel, except
for the camel ride, which I'm

00:44:28.760 --> 00:44:30.730
sure no Israeli would ever do.

00:44:30.730 --> 00:44:34.290
The Bedouin have a camel
ride in the desert.

00:44:34.290 --> 00:44:36.380
You go in the bus,
and they stop,

00:44:36.380 --> 00:44:39.132
and there's like a train
of camels with saddles,

00:44:39.132 --> 00:44:40.090
and then you go around.

00:44:40.090 --> 00:44:42.760
And what I remember,
was when they give you

00:44:42.760 --> 00:44:45.850
the little lecture-- the safety
lecture-- the Bedouin guy.

00:44:45.850 --> 00:44:49.250
When you climb onto
the saddle, he goes,

00:44:49.250 --> 00:44:51.175
do not scream when
camel is getting up.

00:44:51.175 --> 00:44:53.120
Camel is getting
up a little funny.

00:44:53.120 --> 00:44:56.822
And I'm going, like,
how bad can it-- Waah!

00:44:56.822 --> 00:44:58.280
But after, like,
riding just, like,

00:44:58.280 --> 00:45:00.196
a quarter of a mile on
a camel, which is not

00:45:00.196 --> 00:45:01.570
a comfortable
ride, I'm thinking,

00:45:01.570 --> 00:45:04.546
no wonder the Middle
East is so tense.

00:45:04.546 --> 00:45:07.850
If this is how people
are getting around.

00:45:07.850 --> 00:45:09.480
Anyway, thank you.

00:45:09.480 --> 00:45:10.190
Yeah?

00:45:10.190 --> 00:45:10.730
AUDIENCE: Thanks for coming.

00:45:10.730 --> 00:45:10.940
DAVE BARRY: Yeah.

00:45:10.940 --> 00:45:12.540
AUDIENCE: So I told my family
that you were speaking here

00:45:12.540 --> 00:45:15.096
today, and my dad said, wow,
well, your younger brother--

00:45:15.096 --> 00:45:16.470
who's a freshman
in high school--

00:45:16.470 --> 00:45:18.303
has a writing assignment
to write an article

00:45:18.303 --> 00:45:20.260
in the style of Dave Barry.

00:45:20.260 --> 00:45:22.730
So you're still influencing
many high schoolers today.

00:45:22.730 --> 00:45:24.688
DAVE BARRY: Which is a
little terrifying to me.

00:45:24.688 --> 00:45:27.825
Over the years, I've
heard that many times.

00:45:27.825 --> 00:45:29.500
The one thing that
I hate the most,

00:45:29.500 --> 00:45:32.410
is when the teacher
assigns them, read this,

00:45:32.410 --> 00:45:34.320
he's a great American humorist.

00:45:34.320 --> 00:45:37.927
Like, when I heard
that from my teachers,

00:45:37.927 --> 00:45:40.010
I already hated whoever
it was that I had to read.

00:45:40.010 --> 00:45:42.000
You know?

00:45:42.000 --> 00:45:43.880
And like, every now
and then, the teacher

00:45:43.880 --> 00:45:47.210
will send me a whole
batch of-- the students

00:45:47.210 --> 00:45:50.630
all had to write something
to me, like, you know,

00:45:50.630 --> 00:45:51.400
about my essay.

00:45:51.400 --> 00:45:53.190
And usually it's just like, I
read your essay, it was funny.

00:45:53.190 --> 00:45:55.890
Sometimes it was like, I
didn't think it was that good.

00:45:55.890 --> 00:45:59.395
Well, fuck you, kid, I
didn't ask you to read it.

00:45:59.395 --> 00:46:02.010
It wasn't my idea that you
had to read this thing.

00:46:02.010 --> 00:46:02.670
I'm sorry.

00:46:02.670 --> 00:46:05.830
I don't mean your
brother or sister.

00:46:05.830 --> 00:46:08.180
AUDIENCE: I'll let you know
what his sentiments are.

00:46:08.180 --> 00:46:10.410
But related to your
style, have you

00:46:10.410 --> 00:46:11.854
found that that
voice in your head

00:46:11.854 --> 00:46:14.020
has remained essentially
the same since high school?

00:46:14.020 --> 00:46:15.478
Or have you
consciously adapted it?

00:46:15.478 --> 00:46:18.162
Or has it become more optimistic
or more cynical over the years?

00:46:18.162 --> 00:46:19.620
DAVE BARRY: I get
asked that a lot.

00:46:19.620 --> 00:46:20.599
I don't really know.

00:46:20.599 --> 00:46:22.390
I don't feel as though
I've changed at all.

00:46:22.390 --> 00:46:23.860
I must have changed,
because I've

00:46:23.860 --> 00:46:27.600
been doing this for like, what,
40 years, something like that.

00:46:27.600 --> 00:46:29.870
I don't feel any differently.

00:46:29.870 --> 00:46:33.530
If I have changed, it's
been pretty gradual.

00:46:33.530 --> 00:46:35.560
I still feel basically
that what I do

00:46:35.560 --> 00:46:39.310
is I write silly humor,
rather than satire,

00:46:39.310 --> 00:46:43.470
which I always viewed as
humor that was not funny.

00:46:43.470 --> 00:46:45.560
Or meaningful,
point making humor.

00:46:45.560 --> 00:46:48.580
I'm just looking for
the next easy joke.

00:46:48.580 --> 00:46:51.475
I'm not really trying
to help anybody.

00:46:51.475 --> 00:46:54.810
And every now and then somebody
will say to me, you know,

00:46:54.810 --> 00:46:56.887
people, when I laughed,
it made me feel better.

00:46:56.887 --> 00:46:58.720
I was going through a
tough time in my life,

00:46:58.720 --> 00:47:00.195
and I read your stuff,
and I felt better.

00:47:00.195 --> 00:47:01.790
Or I got along
better with my son.

00:47:01.790 --> 00:47:03.160
And I said, that's great,
but I would have done it

00:47:03.160 --> 00:47:04.805
even if it made you feel worse.

00:47:04.805 --> 00:47:07.850
Because it's the only
skill I actually have.

00:47:07.850 --> 00:47:08.350
Anyway.

00:47:08.350 --> 00:47:09.485
I don't think I've changed much.

00:47:09.485 --> 00:47:10.420
AUDIENCE: All right,
well, keep it up, then.

00:47:10.420 --> 00:47:11.670
DAVE BARRY: Thank you, I will.

00:47:11.670 --> 00:47:12.230
Yeah?

00:47:12.230 --> 00:47:13.120
AUDIENCE: Hi, thank
you for coming.

00:47:13.120 --> 00:47:14.290
DAVE BARRY: No,
it's my pleasure.

00:47:14.290 --> 00:47:15.998
AUDIENCE: My dad and
I read your articles

00:47:15.998 --> 00:47:17.640
as well, very consistently.

00:47:17.640 --> 00:47:19.806
I read "Tricky Business"
and "Big Trouble,"

00:47:19.806 --> 00:47:21.680
and I think I have a
very good sense of-- you

00:47:21.680 --> 00:47:23.382
have a very distinct voice.

00:47:23.382 --> 00:47:25.340
And somehow I totally
missed that "Big Trouble"

00:47:25.340 --> 00:47:26.522
was made into a movie.

00:47:26.522 --> 00:47:28.480
Someone tells me about
it, and I'm like, oh no.

00:47:28.480 --> 00:47:29.938
Oh no, they're
going to mess it up.

00:47:29.938 --> 00:47:32.955
There's no way they're going to
capture his voice in film form.

00:47:32.955 --> 00:47:34.437
And I was so happy
that it really

00:47:34.437 --> 00:47:36.270
felt like it was your
writing in movie form.

00:47:36.270 --> 00:47:37.686
DAVE BARRY: I'm
glad you liked it.

00:47:37.686 --> 00:47:41.950
There actually is, in my
Russia essay, in this book.

00:47:41.950 --> 00:47:45.215
"Big Trouble" is-- I wrote
a novel set in Florida

00:47:45.215 --> 00:47:48.310
called "Big Trouble," where
basically a couple of losers

00:47:48.310 --> 00:47:52.140
get hold of a nuclear
bomb suitcase.

00:47:52.140 --> 00:47:55.430
They think it's emeralds,
but it's a nuclear weapon.

00:47:55.430 --> 00:47:59.262
And this was
hilarious madcap plot.

00:47:59.262 --> 00:48:01.720
The only problem is that the
movie was supposed to come out

00:48:01.720 --> 00:48:04.970
on September 12, 2001.

00:48:04.970 --> 00:48:05.920
The day after 9/11.

00:48:05.920 --> 00:48:08.910
And so you're not
going to have a madcap

00:48:08.910 --> 00:48:13.300
comedy about a bomb in a plane
come out after-- nobody gets

00:48:13.300 --> 00:48:15.290
killed in the movie or
in the book-- but still,

00:48:15.290 --> 00:48:16.260
it was just all wrong.

00:48:16.260 --> 00:48:18.450
So the movie came
out kind of, like,

00:48:18.450 --> 00:48:20.430
secretly six months later.

00:48:20.430 --> 00:48:22.880
And it didn't make
much of a ripple.

00:48:22.880 --> 00:48:24.960
It became sort of a
cult-- you can still

00:48:24.960 --> 00:48:29.030
see it on TV, sometimes.

00:48:29.030 --> 00:48:32.710
But when I went to
Russia, the one thing

00:48:32.710 --> 00:48:36.030
I learned from the talks Ridley
and I gave around Russia.

00:48:36.030 --> 00:48:39.100
I would always ask
them, what do they

00:48:39.100 --> 00:48:40.940
think our stereotypical
views of them are.

00:48:40.940 --> 00:48:43.910
What are their
stereotypical views of us?

00:48:43.910 --> 00:48:46.300
Their stereotypical
views of was always like,

00:48:46.300 --> 00:48:48.530
we're a bunch of consumer
obsessed people who

00:48:48.530 --> 00:48:49.738
don't care about [INAUDIBLE].

00:48:49.738 --> 00:48:51.780
You know, totally
accurate, to be honest.

00:48:51.780 --> 00:48:53.680
And they always
said ours of them

00:48:53.680 --> 00:48:56.910
was that they are vodka
drinking, balaklava

00:48:56.910 --> 00:48:59.632
playing gangsters.

00:48:59.632 --> 00:49:01.590
I heard the word gangsters
over and over again.

00:49:01.590 --> 00:49:05.590
So the last night I was there,
we were in St Petersburg.

00:49:05.590 --> 00:49:08.180
And we were at the
American consulate,

00:49:08.180 --> 00:49:10.670
where they have, once
a month, a movie night,

00:49:10.670 --> 00:49:12.600
where they bring
in Russian citizens

00:49:12.600 --> 00:49:14.920
and show them American movies.

00:49:14.920 --> 00:49:16.820
These usually people
who speak some English.

00:49:16.820 --> 00:49:19.070
And it's meant to just build
relations between the two

00:49:19.070 --> 00:49:19.800
countries.

00:49:19.800 --> 00:49:22.399
And usually it's some
traditional American classic.

00:49:22.399 --> 00:49:23.940
But because I was
there, they decided

00:49:23.940 --> 00:49:26.210
to show them "Big Trouble".

00:49:26.210 --> 00:49:27.434
Which was fine.

00:49:27.434 --> 00:49:29.350
And then he said, would
you introduce the book

00:49:29.350 --> 00:49:31.330
to the crowd, and then
answer questions after?

00:49:31.330 --> 00:49:32.038
And I said, sure.

00:49:32.038 --> 00:49:34.360
So I get up in front of
all of these Russians.

00:49:34.360 --> 00:49:38.795
And I just gone over the
plot, because I hadn't seen it

00:49:38.795 --> 00:49:39.680
in years.

00:49:39.680 --> 00:49:41.520
And I realized that
there are Russians

00:49:41.520 --> 00:49:44.300
in-- the good news is there
are Russians in this movie.

00:49:44.300 --> 00:49:47.610
The bad news is
they're gangsters.

00:49:47.610 --> 00:49:49.890
The only Russian
characters in movie.

00:49:49.890 --> 00:49:52.242
Because it was based on an
actual incident in Miami,

00:49:52.242 --> 00:49:53.950
where they closed down
a bar in Jai-Alai,

00:49:53.950 --> 00:49:56.650
which was Russians
selling surplus

00:49:56.650 --> 00:50:02.267
Soviet illegally obtained
military weaponry.

00:50:02.267 --> 00:50:03.850
And I turned them
into people who were

00:50:03.850 --> 00:50:05.862
selling a nuclear suitcase.

00:50:05.862 --> 00:50:08.460
But anyway, I had to get up in
front of all these Russians,

00:50:08.460 --> 00:50:10.250
and say, there are
Russians in it.

00:50:10.250 --> 00:50:11.090
So, big smiles.

00:50:11.090 --> 00:50:11.840
They're gangsters.

00:50:11.840 --> 00:50:14.132
You know, like.

00:50:14.132 --> 00:50:15.590
But they're really
smart gangsters.

00:50:15.590 --> 00:50:17.800
The American gangsters
are stupid in my movie.

00:50:17.800 --> 00:50:19.480
So I don't know if
that mollified them.

00:50:19.480 --> 00:50:22.129
Did you have a question, or am
I just blithering away up here?

00:50:22.129 --> 00:50:23.170
AUDIENCE: That was great.

00:50:23.170 --> 00:50:26.239
But I was curious how
much influence you

00:50:26.239 --> 00:50:27.530
were able to have in the movie.

00:50:27.530 --> 00:50:30.780
And also being a fan of
your "Peter and the" series,

00:50:30.780 --> 00:50:33.775
hearing that that may be
becoming a movie as well.

00:50:33.775 --> 00:50:35.900
If you'll be able to
influence that in the same way

00:50:35.900 --> 00:50:37.108
you influenced "Big Trouble"?

00:50:37.108 --> 00:50:38.960
DAVE BARRY: With the
movie, not really much.

00:50:38.960 --> 00:50:40.810
I mean, I got to hang around
and watch them make it,

00:50:40.810 --> 00:50:41.393
which was fun.

00:50:41.393 --> 00:50:44.250
And see how ridiculously
the amount of money

00:50:44.250 --> 00:50:47.169
they spend on things like
food when they make a movie.

00:50:47.169 --> 00:50:48.960
And Barry Sonnenfeld,
who was the director,

00:50:48.960 --> 00:50:49.793
was very nice to me.

00:50:49.793 --> 00:50:52.419
And he allowed me
free access to the set

00:50:52.419 --> 00:50:54.710
at all times, which I later
learned was because I never

00:50:54.710 --> 00:50:55.620
suggested anything.

00:50:55.620 --> 00:50:57.320
Usually they don't want the
writer anywhere near it,

00:50:57.320 --> 00:50:58.730
because they change everything.

00:50:58.730 --> 00:50:59.980
You sort of get used to that.

00:50:59.980 --> 00:51:02.372
"Peter and the Star
Catchers," I don't know

00:51:02.372 --> 00:51:03.580
that it will ever be a movie.

00:51:03.580 --> 00:51:04.580
There was talk that it would be.

00:51:04.580 --> 00:51:06.190
This is the prequel
to "Peter Pan,"

00:51:06.190 --> 00:51:07.880
that I wrote with a guy named
Ridley Pearson, the guy I

00:51:07.880 --> 00:51:08.890
went to Russia with.

00:51:08.890 --> 00:51:10.680
And we end up running
a bunch of books.

00:51:10.680 --> 00:51:12.510
It did become a
Broadway play-- which

00:51:12.510 --> 00:51:15.250
won five Tony awards-- called
"Peter and the Starcatcher."

00:51:15.250 --> 00:51:18.180
And it's still touring
the country as a play.

00:51:18.180 --> 00:51:20.810
The play was adapted by a
guy named Rick Ellis, who

00:51:20.810 --> 00:51:21.690
wrote "Jersey Boys."

00:51:21.690 --> 00:51:23.981
And it's actually a lot
funnier than the book we wrote.

00:51:23.981 --> 00:51:26.900
We wrote sort of a
straightforward kids' adventure

00:51:26.900 --> 00:51:27.650
story.

00:51:27.650 --> 00:51:31.699
And Rick made it for grownups,
and very, very funny.

00:51:31.699 --> 00:51:33.240
Anyway, that's what
happened to that.

00:51:33.240 --> 00:51:35.610
Thank you.

00:51:35.610 --> 00:51:37.050
AUDIENCE: Thanks for coming.

00:51:37.050 --> 00:51:38.460
DAVE BARRY: Everybody says that.

00:51:38.460 --> 00:51:39.370
You're very polite.

00:51:39.370 --> 00:51:40.940
I mean, I had to come.

00:51:40.940 --> 00:51:43.045
Katie McKee, back
there, my publicist,

00:51:43.045 --> 00:51:45.170
made me come here, because
she wants the food here.

00:51:45.170 --> 00:51:46.169
She likes the cafeteria.

00:51:49.466 --> 00:51:50.840
AUDIENCE: I had
a simple question

00:51:50.840 --> 00:51:54.170
about how do you think
the-- generally, when

00:51:54.170 --> 00:51:57.770
I try to show American
humor to my parents, who

00:51:57.770 --> 00:52:04.356
are from India, they kind of
think, like, that's very banal.

00:52:04.356 --> 00:52:05.730
It's not really--
They don't even

00:52:05.730 --> 00:52:08.600
laugh at, like, things
which I laugh at.

00:52:08.600 --> 00:52:10.990
And I find it really wise.

00:52:10.990 --> 00:52:13.490
Some say, for example, all
the beer is much faster.

00:52:13.490 --> 00:52:17.725
I would tell it to my parents,
and they would say, hmm, OK.

00:52:17.725 --> 00:52:19.350
DAVE BARRY: You need
new friends, dude.

00:52:22.100 --> 00:52:24.050
AUDIENCE: What are
the general humor

00:52:24.050 --> 00:52:27.030
that you have found, since
you have presented at Russia--

00:52:27.030 --> 00:52:28.490
you covered a lot of Russia.

00:52:28.490 --> 00:52:30.989
I was hoping to look through,
like, all right, India, India,

00:52:30.989 --> 00:52:31.610
no, no.

00:52:31.610 --> 00:52:33.210
DAVE BARRY: I
didn't get to India.

00:52:33.210 --> 00:52:35.990
AUDIENCE: And so what
are the sets of humor

00:52:35.990 --> 00:52:37.650
that you find-- say,
satire is probably

00:52:37.650 --> 00:52:39.800
not-- you do mention
that it's not probably

00:52:39.800 --> 00:52:40.670
that cross cutting.

00:52:40.670 --> 00:52:42.280
Try talking satire
to your girlfriend,

00:52:42.280 --> 00:52:44.221
and making, not so much.

00:52:44.221 --> 00:52:44.720
Right?

00:52:44.720 --> 00:52:47.980
So that actually works across
all cultures very well.

00:52:47.980 --> 00:52:50.490
And what are some which
don't really jell,

00:52:50.490 --> 00:52:52.275
and they sometimes
insult people.

00:52:52.275 --> 00:52:55.370
DAVE BARRY: Yeah, I've
never really been sure.

00:52:55.370 --> 00:52:57.970
The only foreign country
where my humor has,

00:52:57.970 --> 00:53:01.830
I know, has done reasonably
well, is England.

00:53:01.830 --> 00:53:05.440
And as you probably know,
they speak English over there.

00:53:05.440 --> 00:53:07.353
Not as well as we
do, in my-- no.

00:53:10.587 --> 00:53:11.670
Even then, it's difficult.

00:53:14.760 --> 00:53:17.860
The first book tour
I went on in England.

00:53:17.860 --> 00:53:20.410
They all think we're
idiots, I mean, the Brits,

00:53:20.410 --> 00:53:21.160
in terms of humor.

00:53:21.160 --> 00:53:23.780
They think they are way more
sophisticated than we are.

00:53:23.780 --> 00:53:26.680
And maybe they
are, I don't know.

00:53:26.680 --> 00:53:28.200
But they feel that
American humor,

00:53:28.200 --> 00:53:32.230
it tends to be primitive,
and they're much more attuned

00:53:32.230 --> 00:53:34.189
to sarcasm and irony.

00:53:34.189 --> 00:53:35.230
Again, they may be right.

00:53:35.230 --> 00:53:36.710
But I remember, I
went on a book tour.

00:53:36.710 --> 00:53:38.001
I don't even remember the book.

00:53:38.001 --> 00:53:40.060
This was, like, a long time ago.

00:53:40.060 --> 00:53:43.780
And I would go into BBC
show after BBC show,

00:53:43.780 --> 00:53:44.700
that's all I did.

00:53:44.700 --> 00:53:46.200
And I would get
into a little studio

00:53:46.200 --> 00:53:49.590
with a very well educated
BBC guy, who would

00:53:49.590 --> 00:53:51.309
speak much better than I did.

00:53:51.309 --> 00:53:52.850
And we'd do an
interview for an hour.

00:53:52.850 --> 00:53:54.550
And then I go out and get in
a car, drive through London

00:53:54.550 --> 00:53:55.720
traffic for an hour.

00:53:55.720 --> 00:53:57.470
And go back into, what
looked to me, like,

00:53:57.470 --> 00:53:58.970
exactly the same room.

00:53:58.970 --> 00:54:00.320
Maybe even the same BBC guy.

00:54:00.320 --> 00:54:00.820
You know?

00:54:00.820 --> 00:54:02.190
They have, like, 300 shows.

00:54:02.190 --> 00:54:03.280
And do another.

00:54:03.280 --> 00:54:06.270
But what I remember was, this
book-- "The New York Times"

00:54:06.270 --> 00:54:09.740
had run a book review where
some reviewer who didn't even

00:54:09.740 --> 00:54:11.200
work for "The New
York Times" said,

00:54:11.200 --> 00:54:13.990
Mr Barry is the
funniest man in America.

00:54:13.990 --> 00:54:18.094
And so, of course every,
publicity person ever

00:54:18.094 --> 00:54:19.760
since used that quote.
"New York Times,"

00:54:19.760 --> 00:54:20.670
funniest man in America.

00:54:20.670 --> 00:54:21.840
It really wasn't
"The New York Times,"

00:54:21.840 --> 00:54:23.425
and who cares what "The
New York Times" thinks

00:54:23.425 --> 00:54:24.258
about humor, anyway?

00:54:26.740 --> 00:54:31.280
But every single BBC interviewer
would start this way,

00:54:31.280 --> 00:54:35.500
our next guest
has been described

00:54:35.500 --> 00:54:40.400
as the funniest man in America.

00:54:40.400 --> 00:54:44.810
Which was like,
we'll see about that.

00:54:44.810 --> 00:54:46.161
And would have to win them over.

00:54:46.161 --> 00:54:46.660
You know?

00:54:46.660 --> 00:54:47.610
So it was painful.

00:54:47.610 --> 00:54:50.210
But that's the only country
where I'm sure of it.

00:54:50.210 --> 00:54:54.850
I, every day practically, get
a book of mine in the mail,

00:54:54.850 --> 00:54:58.369
that the publishers have to
send you when it gets published.

00:54:58.369 --> 00:55:00.410
And half the time I don't
even know what the book

00:55:00.410 --> 00:55:01.701
is, since I can't even read it.

00:55:01.701 --> 00:55:04.720
It's not even in our alphabet.

00:55:04.720 --> 00:55:07.467
So I don't know what book it is.

00:55:07.467 --> 00:55:08.800
I have no idea what it's saying.

00:55:08.800 --> 00:55:11.240
I have no if anybody thinks
it's funny anywhere, at all.

00:55:11.240 --> 00:55:13.480
I just don't know.

00:55:13.480 --> 00:55:15.720
But I think you should
tell everyone in India

00:55:15.720 --> 00:55:17.820
to buy my book and find out.

00:55:17.820 --> 00:55:19.240
Thank you.

00:55:19.240 --> 00:55:19.740
Yeah.

00:55:19.740 --> 00:55:22.740
AUDIENCE: Thank you for coming.

00:55:22.740 --> 00:55:24.150
DAVE BARRY: No, thank you.

00:55:24.150 --> 00:55:25.730
AUDIENCE: Aw, you're welcome.

00:55:25.730 --> 00:55:28.110
I'm wondering how you
feel about-- you know,

00:55:28.110 --> 00:55:31.065
Florida humor has become more
popular these days, with,

00:55:31.065 --> 00:55:33.050
like, the Florida
Man Twitter account,

00:55:33.050 --> 00:55:34.810
and the Florida Woman
Twitter account.

00:55:34.810 --> 00:55:37.940
And, like, everything that
people from Florida do.

00:55:37.940 --> 00:55:40.472
Like when that guy ate that
person's face, or I don't know,

00:55:40.472 --> 00:55:41.180
whatever they do.

00:55:41.180 --> 00:55:42.471
DAVE BARRY: That was hilarious.

00:55:42.471 --> 00:55:43.096
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:55:43.096 --> 00:55:45.137
Not so much for that person
whose face got eaten.

00:55:45.137 --> 00:55:46.150
But for everybody else.

00:55:46.150 --> 00:55:49.560
I'm wondering how you feel about
Florida humor becoming more,

00:55:49.560 --> 00:55:52.680
like, degenerate and
more mainstream, I guess,

00:55:52.680 --> 00:55:55.610
and different from the, sort
of like, '80s Florida humor,

00:55:55.610 --> 00:55:57.407
where like, it was
mostly cocaine gangsters

00:55:57.407 --> 00:55:58.240
shooting each other.

00:55:58.240 --> 00:55:59.198
DAVE BARRY: I'm for it.

00:55:59.198 --> 00:56:01.580
I mean, in fact, I'm planning
to write a book about it,

00:56:01.580 --> 00:56:03.840
about Florida.

00:56:03.840 --> 00:56:06.860
There is something-- you know,
after all these years there-- I

00:56:06.860 --> 00:56:08.320
used to just say,
well, we're just

00:56:08.320 --> 00:56:09.870
saying that because we're here.

00:56:09.870 --> 00:56:12.600
But I genuinely think there
is something truly unusually

00:56:12.600 --> 00:56:13.910
weird about Florida.

00:56:13.910 --> 00:56:17.610
At one point, we just
overtook California

00:56:17.610 --> 00:56:19.480
in the just weirdness level.

00:56:19.480 --> 00:56:23.230
And there's really no one clear
explanation for what happened,

00:56:23.230 --> 00:56:25.480
except that everybody
who's there is there

00:56:25.480 --> 00:56:27.857
for a bad reason.

00:56:27.857 --> 00:56:29.940
Nobody ever just says, I'm
going to go to Florida,

00:56:29.940 --> 00:56:33.250
and live a clean, upright
life, and be productive.

00:56:33.250 --> 00:56:34.390
That person doesn't exist.

00:56:34.390 --> 00:56:36.098
You know, they went
there because they're

00:56:36.098 --> 00:56:38.240
done with working.

00:56:38.240 --> 00:56:42.260
Or they know that it's easier
to do illegal things there.

00:56:42.260 --> 00:56:46.160
Or you could run for office
in five minutes and win.

00:56:46.160 --> 00:56:50.720
My proposal in Miami was that to
streamline our government, when

00:56:50.720 --> 00:56:53.840
we have an election, we should
swear them in and indict them

00:56:53.840 --> 00:56:56.560
in one ceremony.

00:56:56.560 --> 00:56:59.330
I've been in Miami 30 years,
and like, gee, they come and go.

00:56:59.330 --> 00:57:00.980
People just show up, and
they're suddenly, like,

00:57:00.980 --> 00:57:03.104
pillars of the community,
and then they're in jail.

00:57:05.655 --> 00:57:07.780
In Miami is only one, like,
part of the wilderness.

00:57:07.780 --> 00:57:10.540
Then there's Orlando, which
is its own kind of weird.

00:57:10.540 --> 00:57:11.563
So I'm for it.

00:57:11.563 --> 00:57:15.270
I'm for the prevalence
of Florida awareness

00:57:15.270 --> 00:57:18.470
out there, because I hope
to write a book about it.

00:57:18.470 --> 00:57:21.510
So purely for just venal
reasons, I think it's good.

00:57:21.510 --> 00:57:22.650
AUDIENCE: Makes sense.

00:57:22.650 --> 00:57:23.650
DAVE BARRY: Yeah?

00:57:23.650 --> 00:57:25.150
AUDIENCE: So near
the beginning, you

00:57:25.150 --> 00:57:26.490
said that when you're
in high school,

00:57:26.490 --> 00:57:28.220
you could make farting
noises with your hands.

00:57:28.220 --> 00:57:28.460
DAVE BARRY: Yeah.

00:57:28.460 --> 00:57:30.230
AUDIENCE: Can you still do that?

00:57:30.230 --> 00:57:32.860
DAVE BARRY: Well, could
you hold the microphone?

00:57:36.480 --> 00:57:38.240
I'm not in-- wait!

00:57:38.240 --> 00:57:40.610
That far away?

00:57:40.610 --> 00:57:42.490
[FARTING NOISES]

00:57:44.104 --> 00:57:45.020
DAVE BARRY: Thank you.

00:57:45.020 --> 00:57:46.364
Thank you very much.

00:57:49.230 --> 00:57:51.190
And I'm sure if Joyce
Carol Oates were here,

00:57:51.190 --> 00:57:52.870
you would ask her
to do that, as well.

00:57:52.870 --> 00:57:56.490
Well anyway, I think we're sort
of through the allotted time,

00:57:56.490 --> 00:57:57.810
and well beyond it.

00:57:57.810 --> 00:57:59.150
But thank you all for coming.

00:57:59.150 --> 00:58:01.320
This has been-- I
actually enjoyed this.

00:58:01.320 --> 00:58:03.780
And I don't always say that on
book tour, but this was fun.

00:58:03.780 --> 00:58:05.600
Thank you.

